<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Councils Urged to Step Up Y2K Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The Australian federal
government Tuesday urged local councils to renew their efforts in
dealing with the year 2000 computer bug or Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
A survey published in the latest Local Government National
Report showed that nearly one-third of the local councils surveyed
assessed the risk of the millennium bug to be moderate.
</P>
<P>
The Y2K problem means that, unless adjusted, computerized
systems could be disabled when their internal clocks tick over to
January 1, 2000, as the clocks only recognize years starting with
"19".
</P>
<P>
Local Government Minister Ian Macdonald said 30 percent of the
responding councils indicated that they were either fully prepared
or well advanced in preparations to deal with the bug.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more than a quarter indicated that they were unsure
of their preparations, or only in the early stages of preparations
or had not started at all.
</P>
<P>
"All councils rely on computer-based date tracking systems for
payments, payrolls, customer reminders and other important
information, so this is a matter which requires close management
over the next 12 months," Macdonald said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Other areas which might be affected include building
management systems, security systems, environmental monitoring and
even water and sewerage systems.
</P>
<P>
"While we all look forward to the year 2000 with an air of
anticipation and excitement, many companies, public sector
authorities and councils still have some way to go to deal with
the looming problems of the year 2000 bug," he said.
</P>
<P>
Macdonald said local councils need to ensure they have a
strategy that implements solutions, tests systems and makes
allowances for contingencies to reduce the impact of Y2K-related
problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
