<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fischer: EU Must Reform Itself Before Enlargement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Union has to reform
its finances before taking in new members from the former East
Bloc, German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer said Tuesday on a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
"The EU itself must do its homework in order to complete
eastward expansion," Fischer emphasized.
</P>
<P>
He admitted it would be tough to achieve agreement on a
so-called Agenda 2000 -- reform of the Union's budget, farm
spending and aid to poorer regions.
</P>
<P>
As the current EU's rotating presidency, Germany has pledged to
adopt the Agenda 2000 deal among the bloc's 15 members by late
March, in order to reform the EU's policy of agriculture and
regional development aid.
</P>
<P>
Germany stressed that changing the way of the EU's disbursed
agriculture and regional development aid is a vital condition for
the admission of poorer and more agrarian East European states to
the EU.
</P>
<P>
Bonn is demanding a cut to its net annual contribution of 13
billion dollars to Brussels and has suggested individual EU
members begin picking up part of the farm subsidy bill which
devours nearly half of Union spending. This is fiercely opposed by
France which wants Brussels to remain the paymaster for Europe's
farmers.
</P>
<P>
Fischer denied Bonn had become cooler to enlargement under
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder as compared to ex-Chancellor Helmut
Kohl, and said there could be no doubting of Germany's resolve to
enlarge the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
