<HEADLINE> U.S.,Iraqi Aircraft Confront Over No-Fly Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
WASHINGTON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. defense officials
reported a new incident in the no-fly zone over southern Iraq on
Tuesday, saying none of the U.S. warplanes involved in the
incident were lost.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the U.S. Central Command, Major Joe LaMarca,
said further details are yet to be available as military experts
were still checking reports from the region.
</P>
<P>
Defense officials said no U.S. aircraft were lost. Two F-15s
and two F-14s from the Navy were involved in the confrontation.
</P>
<P>
At least one air-to-air missile was fired at an Iraqi
aircraft in the no-fly zone, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zone was set up after the 1991 Gulf War. The
incident was the third of its kind since the United States and
Britain unleashed air strikes against Iraq last December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
