<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Fires at Iraqi aircraft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. warplanes fired
air-to-air missiles at Iraqi aircraft Tuesday at about 2:30 EST
(0730 GMT) over the northern no-fly zone in Iraq, defense
officials said.
</P>
<P>
One of the officials said one of the Iraqi planes was believed
to have crashed, but apparently not by the U.S. missiles, after
running out of fuel.
</P>
<P>
The American planes -- two Air Force F-15 strike aircraft and
two Navy F-14 fighters -- returned safely to the carrier Carl
Vinson where they took off for patrolling the no-fly zone.
</P>
<P>
David Leavy, spokesman for the White House National Security
Council, said Tuesday that President Bill Clinton had made it
clear the United States would enforce the no-fly zones vigorously.
"The Iraqi violations are at their own peril," he added.
</P>
<P>
The incident marked an escalation of tensions between Iraq and
the United States and Britain over enforcing the "no-fly" zones in
northern and southern Iraq. Iraq considers the restrictions
illegal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
