<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tax Collections Go Up in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Total tax collections
increased by 7 percent to 940 billion rupees (22.12 billion U.S.
dollars) in India during April-December 1998, an official press
release said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
But indirect tax collections continued to decline with customs
duty year-on-year recording a negative 16 percent growth last
month, the release said.
</P>
<P>
The 7 percent growth registered in the first nine months of the
current fiscal year, which began on April 1, was mainly due to
buoyant direct tax collections which went up by 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Indirect tax collections grew by a mere 3 percent in the same
period mainly because of positive growth in excise duty
collections which increased by 10 percent last December as
compared to the same month of 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
