<HEADLINE> King Hussein to Meet Clinton in White House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein of Jordan is
going to call President Bill Clinton at the White House on his way
home from six months of cancer treatment at the Mayo Clinic in
Rochester, Minn.
</P>
<P>
He also plans to go to London when he leaves Washington, and
then back home to Jordan in mid-January.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein has played a supporting role to Clinton at the
talks in Wye Plantation, Maryland, in October that produced an
agreement between Israel and the Palestinians over the Israeli
pullout of a further 13 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has decided
against a trip to Israel because of the suspension of the Wye
agreement. Instead, she sends senior adviser Dennis Ross there.
</P>
<P>
Ross is due to meet in New York this week with Israeli Foreign
Minister Ariel Sharon and will then fly to Israel to speak to and
attend a meeting in Tel Aviv next week of the governing board of
the Peres Center for Peace.
</P>
<P>
James Rubin, spokesman for the State Department, Monday
dismissed an Israeli report that Albright had refused to meet with
Sharon because of the Israeli refusal to implement the Wye accord.
</P>
<P>
"The suggestion that there's some problem between us and the
Israeli Foreign Ministry is simply incorrect," Rubin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
