<HEADLINE> Singapore to Send More Aid to Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore government will
provide 1,000 tons of rice and an amount of medicine in its third
phase of humanitarian assistance to Indonesia, a government
statement said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the aid is part of the 12 million Singapore
dollars (7.27 million U.S. dollars) of rice and medicine for
Indonesia announced by the Singapore government on July 6, 1998
and will be distributed to the people of East and Central Java.
</P>
<P>
The rice and medicine will be shipped to the port of Tanjung
Perak, Surabaya in East Java and to the port of Tanjung Emas,
Semarang in Central Java.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of Singapore's humanitarian aid, comprising
10,000 tons of rice and a supply of medicine, was handed over on
August 6, 1998, to Indonesian Minister for Defense and Security
and Commander of the Armed forces General Wiranto by Singapore
Minister for Education and Second Minister for Defense Teo Chee
Hean.
</P>
<P>
The second batch, which comprised 4,000 tons of rice and a
supply of medicine, was shipped to Indonesia and presented to
Governor of Riau Bapak Soeripto by Edward Lee on October 16, 1998.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
