<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Calls on Eritrea to Accept OAU Peace Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Foreign Minister Seyoum
Mesfin Tuesday called on the international community to put "meaningful and
effective pressure" on Eritrea to force its to accept the peace proposals
endorsed by the summit of Central Organ of the Organization of African
Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news briefing organized for members of the diplomatic
community in Addis Ababa and foreign and local press Tuesday afternoon,
Seyoum said: " It is now almost eight months since the Eritrean aggression
against Ethiopia and since the forceful occupation of Ethiopian territory
by Eritrea."
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian Foreign Minister reviewed peace efforts made by the OAU
and the international community since the border crisis between Ethiopia
and Eritrea took place in May last year and said "The diplomatic effort is
clearly stymied by Eritrean obduracy and intransigence."
</P>
<P>
Seyoum said, the OAU Central Organ Summit held in Ougadougou in mid
December " has placed its proposal on the table and has called for its
speedy implementation."
</P>
<P>
 He stated that "Ethiopia has accepted the proposal", noting that
Eritrea continues to talk about amendments to " the core issue which
demands its withdrawal from Ethiopian territory and the return of the
Ethiopian administration."
</P>
<P>
 He called on the international community to put meaningful and
effective pressure on Eritrea so that the OAU can succeed in its effort to
solve the Ethiopia-Eritrea crisis.
</P>
<P>
 The Central Organ of the OAU Mechansim for Conflict Prevention,
Management and Resolution held its fourth ordinary session at the level of
heads of state and government in Ouagadougou on December 18, 1998. The
Summit endorsed the proposals for a framework agreement, submitted by the
OAU high level delegation, for a peaceful settlement of the dispute between
Eritrean and Ethiopia. The 11-point proposals include immediate cessation
of hostilities, creation of conditions conducive to a comprehensive and
lasting settlement of the conflict, withdrawal of Eritrean troops from
Badme Town and its environs to positions they held before May 6, 1998,
redeployment of a group of military observers and demarcation of the border
between the two countries within six months.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibian-Angolan Border Remains Calm: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The situation along the Angolan-
Namibian border has been calm although there have been sounds of gunfire,
South African Broadcasting Association reported Tuesday. Elise
Haulondjaba, Police Commander for Northern Namibia was quoted as saying
Monday that shooting was heard over the weekend on the Angolan side.
</P>
<P>
Haulondjaba said that the firing occurred in Bongola and Chitala, far
from the common Angolan-Namibian frontier.
</P>
<P>
The police official said that members of the Namibian troops and police
forces had been patrolling the area, and no illegal cross-border activities
have been reported.
</P>
<P>
 Namibian state radio reported last weekend that the armed National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) rebels, who have been
fighting with the government troops, were reportedly to have been seen
guarding the frontier areas and were alleged to be harassing civilians.
</P>
<P>
Namibian police have advised local residents not to graze their cattle
across the Angolan-Namibian border until further notice.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
