<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Lifts Fish Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican Health Ministry announced
Tuesday to Lift the ban on the consumption and processing of fish in
northern Mozambique's Cabo Delgado Province.  Though the province is still
plagued by cholera, the health authorities have not found any cases of food
poisoning related with fish in the past three weeks, the ministry said in a
statement said. It is reported that some fishermen in the areas used
insecticide in catching and processing fish, which resulted in deaths, and
serious illness in the areas since the latter half of 1998. The
government issued an order on December 2, banning the catching and
processing of fish in the province for 45 days. There has been no report
of fish poisoning ever since issuing the ban there, the statement said.
Dried fish in stock in the province can be sold and consumed after tests by
health authorities, the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
