<HEADLINE> U.S. Construction Spending Rises in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. construction spending
rose 0.9 percent in November to a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of 677.8 billion U.S. dollars, the Commerce Department said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time the volatile series posted six
consecutive gains since 1993. And it was the largest increase
since July because of strong gains in housing and government
projects.
</P>
<P>
Low interest rates also have fueled robust construction, both
of new homes and commercial projects, and overall construction
spending in November was 8.8 percent higher than a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
In November, however, commercial spending edged down 0.1
percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 174.6 billion U.S.
dollars, the first decline in four months. Sizable gains in
spending on offices and retail stores did not quite offset big
drops for hotels and motels and factories.
</P>
<P>
Spending on housing jumped 1.2 percent, propelled by a 1.8
percent advance in single-family homes.
</P>
<P>
Increases for schools and streets and highways helped push
government spending up by 2.1 percent in November, almost making
up for a 2.7 percent decline in October.
</P>
<P>
Separately, U.S. manufacturing activity slowed in December for
the seventh straight month as global economic problems continue to
hinder exports.
</P>
<P>
The National Association of Purchasing Management said Monday
that its monthly index of business activity fell to 45.1 percent
last month, down from 46.8 percent in November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
