<HEADLINE> Second Private Radio Station Operational in Lesotho </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Mo-Africa, the second private radio
station in Lesotho has become operational at the beginning this week, South
African Broadcasting Association reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Candy Ramainoane, managing director of the radio, was quoted as saying
that the station, which opens at six o'clock in the morning and closes at
10.30 at night daily, would offer programs of cultural, educational,
political and sports events.
</P>
<P>
Ramainoane said that the launch of his station and the first private
broadcaster, the People's Choice, is a step forward to improve free flow
of information from government control.
</P>
<P>
Ramainoane, who is also a prominent Lesotho journalist, said that he
is happy he has finally accomplished his long-time wish to establish a
private radio station.
</P>
<P>
The Lesotho government controlled the air waves until last year when it
decided to end its monopoly over broadcasting.  
</P>
