<HEADLINE> Footslogger Aims at World Record Stranded in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LUSAKA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- An Angolan footslogger named Lucio Dos
Santos who wants to set a world record by covering 54 African countries is
stranded in Chipata, about 500 kilometers east of Zambian capital Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Dos Santos who arrived in Chipata before Christmas is stranded because
his Panasonic sate lite dish has been stolen, Zambia News Agency ZANA
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with ZANA Tuesday in the eastern city, Dos Santos said
the equipment was stolen from his hospital bed in Chipata General Hospital
where he was admitted to receive medical treatment for his legs that were
nearly paralyzed after walking long distances between Lusaka and Chipata.
</P>
<P>
The footslogger said the loss of the equipment was more of a worry to
him because he could not leave Chipata to continue his travel to Malawi as
the U.S. and South African governments as well as Table Network News (TNN),
Cable News Network (CNN) and British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) were
monitoring his movement by using the equipment that was stolen.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the equipment belonged to the U.S. government and he was
supposed to hand it back on completion of his Africa tour, Dos Santos added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chipata police confirmed receiving a report on the lost
equipment and the U.S. Embassy in Lusaka had been informed about it through
the Angolan Embassy here, said ZANA.
</P>
<P>
Dos Santos began his adventure Africa tour on January 2, 1994 from
South Africa and he has so far covered 50 countries and there are four
others such as Malawi, Mozambique, Swaziland and South Africa to be covered.
</P>
<P>
After arriving in South Africa, the Angolan traveller will fly to Las
Vegas in the U.S. for medical checkup.
</P>
<P>
Dos Santos' African tour is sponsored by Nike, an American company
based in Las Vegas which specializes in sports equipment and by Translux, a
South African bus company.
</P>
<P>
According to his contract with the two sponsors, Dos Santos will give
20 percent of his money that he expects to receive at the end of his tour
to the poor in all the 54 countries he passes through.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
