<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal, India Renew Transit Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Nepal and India agreed here
Tuesday to renew the Treaty of Transit, which guarantees Nepal's
continued but easier access to the transit points and ports in
India for foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
Nepali Minister for Commerce and Youth, Sports and Culture
Purna Bahadur Khadka and visiting Indian Minister of Commerce Ram
Krishna Hegde signed the letters of exchange in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The transit treaty was signed on December 6, 1991 for a period
of seven years. It was extended for one month before its expiry on
December 5, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to renew the treaty up to January 5, 2006,
and a provision for automatic renewal of the treaty for yet
another seven years has been made as requested by Nepal, the
Nepali Ministry of Commerce said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
"With such a provision for automatic renewal, uncertainties and
apprehensions on the continuation of transit facilities at every
time of the expiry of the treaty have been removed," the press
release said.
</P>
<P>
India also agreed to Nepal's demand for reviewing every seven
years the operational modalities as contained in the protocol and
memorandum attached to the treaty, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
It said that under the renewed treaty, the importers and
exporters have been given an option to use open trucks, marine
containers, container trucks or rail wagons for the transportation
of transit goods.
</P>
<P>
Only those transit goods which are specified as sensitive by
the Indian government with prior intimation to the Nepali
government shall be allowed transportation by marine containers,
container trucks or rail wagons, it added.
</P>
<P>
"The provision on the duty insurance has been made applicable
only to the specified sensitive goods both for imports and
exports," the press release said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, importers and exporters trading on the sensitive
goods have also been given the option of submitting bank guarantee
in place of the duty insurance requirements, it added.
</P>
<P>
Both governments have agreed through exchange of letters to
continue the present arrangements and operational modalities for
the transit routes of Radhikapur and Phulbari in India for the
movement of Nepal's transit trade to and through Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Under the renewed treaty, India also agrees to offer additional
leased area at the Calcutta port to Nepal, specify the shortest
road route connecting Calcutta with all the 15 border entry/exit
points and allow importers to submit the original copy of the
Customs Transit Declaration Form after cross border verification
to the concerned Indian border customs instead of the Calcutta
Customs.
</P>
<P>
Indian Commerce Minister Hegde said the renewed treaty would
help promote Nepal's trade with third countries.
</P>
<P>
But he warned that "both of us have to be careful with those
people who would like to create troubles like smuggling and
encouraging terrorists."
</P>
<P>
Nepal and India share a 1,750-kilometer-long border which is
open to each other.
</P>
<P>
As a landlocked country, Nepal depends largely on the transit
points and ports in India for foreign trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0027 </DOCNO>
