<HEADLINE> German Shares, Euro Steady </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 5 (Xinhua) -- German shares retreated on the
Frankfurt Stock Exchange Tuesday following Monday's big gains,
while the euro lost some of its gleam on the second day of
trading.
</P>
<P>
The DAX Index finished at 5,253.91 points, up 1.55 points from
Monday, and had gained some 4 percent one day. The M-DAX of 70
secondary shares finished at 3,975.64 points, down 15.11 points.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the euro, following its strong start Monday, was
largely unchanged against the dollar and pound, but fell against
the yen Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday afternoon, the euro stood at 1.1790 dollars, virtually
unchanged from 1.1789 dollars Monday. The euro rate would convert
into a D-mark/dollar rate of 1.6588 marks per dollar, down from
1.6590 Monday.
</P>
<P>
Against the pound sterling, the euro stood at 0.71220 pounds, up
from 0.7111 pounds.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the euro slipped to 130.96 yen, from Monday's
inaugural 133.73 yen, and also fell to 1.6123 Swiss francs, from
1.6168 francs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ECB announced completion of its first
refinancing operation, providing 75 billion euros at the 3 percent
rate announced by the central bank in December.
</P>
<P>
It said a total of 944 banks had submitted bids totaling 482
billion euros, so that the amount to be disbursed from January
7-20 came to 15.57 percent. 
</P>
