<BODY>
<HEADLINE> economic Growth in Africa Slashed by Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
HARARE, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Africa's steady economic growth over the
last three years has been slashed by almost half partly due to the east
Asian financial crisis, a newsletter of the Alliance for Africa's
Industrialization (AAI) has said.
</P>
<P>
The newsletter, Africa Industrial, said in its latest issue that Africa'
s
trade prospects have been worsened by this crisis due to the huge
devaluations of Asian currencies.
</P>
<P>
"As it is, Africa's declining share of world trade is now below one
percent," said the newsletter which was released here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The newsletter said a major slowdown of Africa's economic growth or
gross domestic product (GDP) occurred last year when it fell to 3.2 percent
from a healthy 5.8 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
For sub-Saharan Africa, it said, GDP growth declined from five percent
in 1996 to 3.5 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
"More ominous is the drop in Africa's export earnings which will be
reduced significantly due to a persistent decline in world commodity prices
by a fifth," said the newsletter.
</P>
<P>
Exports of Africa's textiles, garments, cocoa, wood, rubber, palm oil,
vegetable oils and other products were also hit by more competitive
Asian products following the devaluation of Asian currencies in the wake of
the financial crisis, it said.
</P>
<P>
It said economic recovery of sub-Saharan Africa which started in 1994-
95 will be eroded.
</P>
<P>
"Currently, commodity prices are declining partly due to the Asian
crisis because of weak demand from Asian countries," it said. But, it said,
prices of raw materials and food and beverages may take a positive
turn this year.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign investment in Africa is also adversely affected because
international capital has become more cautious, costly and difficult to
attract," it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
