<HEADLINE> Israeli FM Denies Plot to Oust Netanyahu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 5 (Xinhua) - Israeli Foreign Minister Ariel
Sharon Tuesday denied rumors that he is rallying support from Likud
members and seeking to oust Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in
the upcoming elections.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said Sharon is planning to break away from
Likud and to form a new party in a bid to enable the
right-wingers to win the elections, to be held in May.
</P>
<P>
The reports came after surveys showed that Netanyahu is
chasing after opposition Labor Party leader Ehud Barak by some 10
percentages in opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
The reports said Sharon will try to persuade Likud defectors
Dan Meridor and Benny Begin, who have separately announced their
candidacies for the premiership, and wavering cabinet ministers
Yitzhak Mordechai and Limor Livnat to join his new party.
</P>
<P>
Sharon denied any involvement in such reported conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
He stressed at a meeting of the Likud Central Committee last
month that he will not challenge Netanyahu for prime minister, but
several days later he said he would not rule out the possibility
of entering the race "under exceptional circumstances."
</P>
<P>
The Israeli parliament Monday gave its final approval to early
elections, slated for May 17.
</P>
<P>
However, Finance Ministry officials told the Central Election
Committee Tuesday that there is no budget for the elections
since the parliament has failed to pass the national budget
for 1999 by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
This is the second consecutive year that the country entered a
new year without a budget. Finance Minister Ya'acov Neeman
resigned last month, frustrated by the disarry in the coalition
which hindered the passage of the budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
