<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Resettle 20,000 Flood-Prone Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia announces Tuesday that over
20,000 farmers living in flood-prone areas of the western Gambella Region
will be resettled in five years beginning this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, Deputy head of the Gambella
Region, Gach Ress, said at a press conference held at Gambella Town, some
800 kms west of Addis Ababa, that farmers who are residing along river
banks in the region will be moved to areas where they will be safe from
flood.
</P>
<P>
Gach told press that thousands of these residents have faced repeated
displacements due to irresistible flood occurences.
</P>
<P>
The places where the farmers are to be resettled will be conducive to
farming and are going to supplied with social and economic infrastructures,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The Gambella Region is located at western part of the country,
bordering with the Sudan. The lowlands of the region is vulnerable to be
flooded during heavily rainfalls. 
</P>
</TEXT>
