<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Police on Alert to Preempt Holiday-Related Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The Addis Ababa police commission
said Tuesday that it will tighten security in the Capital city in
connection with the Ethiopian Christmas that will be celebrated Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Commissioner Belete Gulentaw told local press at a press conference
here that policemen will be on the alert at market places, recreation
centers and churches during the Christmas.
</P>
<P>
He said the police are patrolling wide and congested markets, in its
efforts to effectively prevent possible crimes.
</P>
<P>
January 7 is called "Genna" (Ethiopian Christmas) in Ethiopia and
people celebrate Christmas with friends and familiy gatherings. Holiday
celebrating people usually have the traditional meal of doro wot (chicken
Curry) and dabo (bread), and drink tella (beer) and tej (a honey drink
similar to mead).
</P>
<P>
The police announcement is aimed at preempting holiday-related crimes
in the capital city which has more than two million population.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
