<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-05 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Deputy PM Pays Ice-breaking Visit to Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Deputy Prime Minister
Abdel Aziz Dekheel Al-Dekheel Tuesday paid a one-day ice-breaking
visit to Amman in a bid to end the eight-year strains in bilateral
ties following the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Al-Dekheel, also Kuwaiti Minister of State for Cabinet
Affairs, conveyed Jordanian Crown Prince and the Regent Hassan Ibn
Talal a letter from his Kuwaiti counterpart Saad Al-Abdullah
Al-Salem Al-Sabah on bilateral ties and regional issues.
</P>
<P>
Al-Dekheel conveyed good wishes to Jordanian King Hussein, who
is expected to return home soon after cancer treatments in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
He also discussed with Hassan efforts to strengthen bilateral
cooperation and matters of regional concerns, reported the Radio
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Al-Dekheel appreciated Hassan's efforts in
urging Iraq to release more Kuwaiti prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
The Regent made the appeal at an emergency meeting on Iraq by
Arab parliamentarians in Amman on December 27, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Al-Dekheel was the highest-ranking Kuwaiti official to visit
Jordan since Iraq invaded Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait cut off its relations with Jordan as Jordan sided with
Iraq during the war.
</P>
<P>
Analysts in Amman say Al-Dekheel's visit would help build up
the momentum of normalizing bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Foreign Minister Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah
Sunday invited his Jordanian counterpart Abdul Ilah al Khatib to visit
the Gulf emirate.
</P>
<P>
Such a visit would officially melt the ice in bilateral ties,
Sheikh Sabah was quoted as saying by Kuwaiti press.
</P>
<P>
The Marathon rapprochement process began in May 1995, when
Amman apparently distanced itself from Baghdad, and called for
political change in Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
