<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Once Planned to Kill Karadzic: Book </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 5 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
once planned to assassinate the two key Bosnian Serb leaders,
Radovan Karadzic and Ratko Mladic, said a new book published this
week.
</P>
<P>
French journalist Gilles Delafon and American journalist Thomas
Sancton said in their book, "Dear Jacques, Cher Bill," that "a top
military officer of NATO" told them that Chirac raised the
possibility of killing Karadzic and Mladic during a meeting with
U.S. President Bill Clinton in Paris on December 14, 1995.
</P>
<P>
But the two authors said that the revelation was "partially
denied" by the Elysee presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
They quoted an advisor of the French president as saying that
Chirac "would not want to assassinate someone supposed to go on
trial, but it is true that the idea was discussed by the secret
services" of France and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The two authors of the book also said that during a meeting
with Clinton, the then German Chancellor Helmut Kohl and British
Prime Minister Tony Blair in May 1997 in Paris, Chirac suggested
that Karadzic be captured by NATO forces deployed in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
They said that a plan to capture Karadzic, named "Operation
Amber Star," is sleeping "in a deep drawer of an advisor at the
Elysee palace."
</P>
<P>
The plan, which envisages the dispatch of a U.S. commando and a
French commando to capture Karadzic, is still valid, said the two
authors.
</P>
<P>
Delafon, who works for the weekly newspaper Le Journal de
Dimanche, and Sancton, who is Paris bureau chief of the Time
weekly, said they had access to the top officials in the Elysee
palace and the White House. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
