<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arms for NATO Forces in Macedonia Detained in N.Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Customs officials in Greece's
northern port of Thessaloniki have detained 18 containers with a
quantity of arms destined for the NATO multinational force being
deployed in the Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
The customs officials took the action after they found the
cargo was not accompanied by the required shipping documents.
</P>
<P>
The containers with rifles and other light weaponry were loaded
onto a Honduras-flag merchant ship on New Year's Eve together with
other weaponry destined for the 2,000-strong multinational force
being deployed in Macedonia to protect international observers in
the Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
But a customs check revealed that the cargo was not accompanied
by the necessary shipping documents, the semi-official Athens News
Agency (ANA) quoted port authority sources as saying Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The order to detain the containers was given by Thessaloniki
Prosecution Office Director Haralambos Vourliotis immediately
after being alerted by Greece's Merchant Marine Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The cargo was detained until the sender and recipient were
ascertained, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Greek government and military have denied that it was a
case of weapons smuggling.
</P>
<P>
It would be very difficult, if not impossible, for someone to
try to smuggle weapons on a ship transporting weaponry to the
multinational force via the port of Thessaloniki which was now
full of NATO officials and where stringent checks were being
carried out, a Greek military source said.
</P>
<P>
Massive quantities of military equipment are currently being
shipped to Macedonia via Thessaloniki for the multinational force,
which is expected to be fully deployed by mid-January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
