<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-05 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank to Offer Soft Loan to Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank will offer Egypt
600 million U.S. dollars soft loan for the implementation of
projects in the coming 18 months, resident representative of the
bank Khaled Akram said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Akram told Egypt's Middle East News Agency that the country's
economic and political stability and growing international
confidence in its economy encouraged the bank to finance the
projects proposed by the Egyptian government.
</P>
<P>
Egypt started in 1991 economic reforms sponsored by the World
Bank and the International Monetary Fund, loosening control over
and privatizing state-run enterprises. Since then, Egypt's economy
has grown from 2 percent to more than 5 percent and inflation
fallen from 20 percent to under 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Egypt attracted about 2 billion dollars of foreign investment
in 1998 due to its sound investment environment. Many
multinational companies have been cooperating with the country in
its oil and gas fields and promising projects.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank official said the bank will focus, in the coming
phase, on financing Egypt's infrastructure, health, education and
social projects.
</P>
<P>
Of the 600 million dollars, 100 million dollars will be used in
irrigation and drainage projects in some Delta governorates aimed
at improving agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has decided to offer 80 million dollars to
improve the infrastructure in southern Egypt and increase the
number of small projects in a bid to reduce unemployment and
promoting the standard of living there.
</P>
<P>
In cooperation with Egypt's Ministry of Electricity, the bank
is to provide 20 million dollars to a project to generate
electricity with diesel.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 300 million dollars will be offered to farmers for
the use of state-of-the-art technology in farming and improving
agricultural production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
