<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Fishermen to Continue Strike Against EU Directive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Greek fishermen decided Tuesday
to continue their strike in protest against a European Union (EU)
directive limiting fishing zone.
</P>
<P>
The fishermen are protesting against EU directive 1626 which
effectively reduces the distance from the coast in which fishing
is permitted and increases the mesh size of nets.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Panhellenic Union of Trawler Owners decided not
to go out fishing Tuesday and Thursday and to moor their boats in
protest along the Thessaloniki seafront, as they did Monday.
</P>
<P>
Fishermen said that implementation of the measure would result
in a 50 percent reduction in fish catch because smaller-sized fish
would escape their nets, but the Turkish trawlers would continue
to catch those fish and channel them to the Greek market.
</P>
<P>
Trawler owners in Greece are seeking postponement of
implementation of the directive until May 31, when the fishing
season ends for trawlers, and immediate commencement of procedures
for its amendment or indefinite postponement.
</P>
<P>
The panhellenic Union of Trawler Owners numbers more than 190
members who own some 150 trawlers that supply all the fish markets
in Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
