<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Commits to Objective of Humanitarian Program in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council Tuesday said that it would commit itself to the
objective of the humanitarian program in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the Security Council was briefed on the
humanitarian situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Council President Celso Amorim of Brazil
said, "There was a general expression of commitment to the
objective of the humanitarian program and to the importance of
meeting the humanitarian meeds of Iraqi people among the council
members."
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. diplomats, the council Tuesday morning also
considered Iraq's request that the Untied Nations replace American
and British relief staff working in the country.
</P>
<P>
The diplomats said U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan will make
formal response to Iraq's request by stressing that it is the
Untied Nations that decides the international humanitarian workers
in Iraq, and the council is expected to meet on Iraq during the
following days.
</P>
<P>
Iraq Monday officially asked the the United Nations to replace
one American and 13 British humanitarian workers in the country on
grounds that it could not guarantee their safety because of
widespread anger since last month's air strikes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
