<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lockerbie, Iraq to Be Discussed Between S. Africa, Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The Lockerbie impasse, trade, Iraq,
and African conflicts will be among issues discussed when British Prime
Minister Tony Blair visits South Africa this week, South African officials
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Foreign Minister Aziz Pahad told reporters that it was of great
importance that the impasse on the Lockerbie bombing be resolved as it was
creating a climate conducive to further terrorist acts.
</P>
<P>
The bombing of a Pan America airliner in 1988 over the Scottish town of
Lockerbie killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
Pahad said South Africa welcomed a recent agreement by Britain and the
United States to hold the trial of two Libyan bombing suspects in The Hague,
 the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to get a briefing by the (British) prime minister on what they
perceive to be more outstanding problems so that we can, if necessary,
discuss this with the Libyan government.
</P>
<P>
"We will convey to them what the Libyans see as obstacles and I am sure
we will discuss what the British government sees as obstacles to having the
trial started," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pahad said everything possible should be done to ensure that the
suspects were delivered to the Netherlands for trial as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Blair would reportedly ask South African President Nelson Mandela to
intervene personally on the matter when the two leaders meet.
</P>
<P>
Essop Pahad, deputy minister in the office of Deputy President Thabo
Mbeki, said that the United Kingdom-South African Bilateral Forum meeting,
due to take place Thursday, would serve to strengthen ties between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
An important aspect of the meeting would be the signing of a
declaration of intent on industrial cooperation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Other matters on the agenda included European Union-South African trade
negotiations, and the Commonwealth Conference due to be held in November
this year.
</P>
<P>
He announced that Britain's Queen Elizabeth II would attend the
conference and pay a state visit to South Africa at the same time.
</P>
<P>
Pahad said Britain was South Africa's largest investor, and welcomed an
announcement by Blair that Britain would invest 40 billion Rand (6.8
billion U.S. Dollars) in the country.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are still discussing how the money would be invested.
</P>
<P>
The two countries were also expected to discuss the recent U.S. and
British bombings of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Aziz Pahad said South Africa supported a United Nations resolution that
Iraq dismantle its weapons of mass destruction, but disagreed with the
bombings.
</P>
<P>
"Our own information convinces us that the bombing does not solve the
problem and does not serve the objectives of destruction of the Iraqi
weapons of destruction, and neither does it serve the stated objective of
removing Saddam (Hussein)."
</P>
<P>
The conflicts in Angola and the Democratic Republic of the Congo were
also on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
Pahad said South Africa would brief Blair on African efforts to end the
conflicts and seek international support for the continent's initiatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
