<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-05 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Warplanes Violate Iraqi Air Space Again, Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 5 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi military spokesman
said Tuesday U.S. warplanes again violated Iraqi airspace, Iraqi
News Agency INA reported.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said formations of U.S. warplanes flying
from Saudi Arabia and Kuwait violated Iraqi airspace in the
so-called no-fly zone over southern Iraq at 8:56 a.m. local time
(5:56 a.m. GMT).
</P>
<P>
He added that when Iraqi warplanes confronted them at 10:23
a.m. local time (7:23 a.m. GMT), the U.S. planes fled back to
their bases.
</P>
<P>
This is believed to be the first time that Iraqi warplanes
confronted U.S. warplanes over the no-fly zone since its
imposition.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman confirmed all Iraqi warplanes returned to their
bases safely.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. official said earlier Tuesday that one Iraqi plane was
believed to have crashed, apparently after running out of fuel in
the confrontation with U.S. warplanes.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain imposed no-fly zones over northern and
southern Iraq after the 1991 Gulf War with a claimed aim of
protecting the minority Kurds in the north and Shiite Moslems in
the south from the Iraqi central government's oppression.
</P>
<P>
Iraq considers the no-fly zones illegal and has vowed recently
to fire at U.S.-British warplanes patrolling there.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of last month, Iraqi air-defense forces and
U.S.-British warplanes patrolling the no-fly zones have exchanged
fire several times, leading to the deaths of five Iraqis and
injury of another nine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
