<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Sao Tome &AMP; Principe Prime Minister Sworn in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Posser was sworn in by President Miguel Trovoada.
</P>
<P>
In his administrative program, Posser pledged that his government will
adopt a policy of cutting government expenditure in a bid to revitalize the
economy of the tiny west African country.
</P>
<P>
The new prime minster pointed out that after an era of successive
military coups, the government must firmly crack down on corrupts and re-
establish the authority of the state.
</P>
<P>
He said that his government will commit itself to changing the abject
poverty in Sao Tome and Principe by attaching importance to the development
of agriculture and the exploration of off-shore oil.
</P>
<P>
The Movement for the Liberation of Sao Tome and Principe-Social
Democratic Party (MLSTP-PSD) won 31 out of the 55 seats in parliament on
November 8. Therefore, all the cabinet ministers are from the party.
</P>
<P>
Posser, 45, a vice-president of the MLSTP, is a former foreign minister
and former ambassador to Brussels.
</P>
<P>
He replaced Raul Braganca Neto as prime minister of the twin-island
state, a former Portuguese colony which is one of the poorest countries in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
The other new ministers include Foreign Minister Alberto Paulino,
Justice Minister Paulo Jorge de Espirito, Planning Minister Afonso Varela
da Silva, Defense Minister Joao Quaresma Bixigas, Economy Minister Maria
das Neves Baptist and Interior Minister Manuel Marcal Lima. 
</P>
