<HEADLINE> Iraq Accuses U.S. of Lying on Dissidents Execution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Iraq on Tuesday accused the
U.S. of spreading lies that Iraq had arrested Shiite Moslem
dissidents in southern Iraq and executed hundreds of them.
</P>
<P>
An Iraqi spokesman for the Ministry of Information and Culture
was quoted by the Iraqi News Agency as saying the allegations
were aimed at covering the U.S. failure in achieving the goals for
its latest aggression against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department Spokesman James Rubin said earlier
Tuesday that there had been reports of mass arrests in the Shiite
region of southern Iraq over the past six weeks in addition to
hundreds of executions of dissidents at two prisons.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi spokesman said that the U.S. was playing the game of
changing the subject, "a flagrant game which had been played by
(U.S. President Bill) Clinton himself when he ordered the attack
on Iraq to avert the world attention from his shameful scandal
and impeachment proceeding."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain raided Iraq on December 16-19 for four
consecutive nights in an operation code-named "Desert Fox."
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-British attacks killed hundreds of children, women and
elderly people, and by striking Iraq, the U.S. had separate itself
from the framework of the international legitimacy, said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The White House bears hatred toward Iraq and by launching the
continuous aggressions on Iraq and imposing the unjust embargo,
the U.S. remains antagonistic to Iraqi people and its leadership,
said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed sanctions on Iraq following its 1990 invasion
of Kuwait, which touched off the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
"U.S. officials have felt the bitterness of failure these
days, therefore they searched in their old notebooks for news and
information which they feel serve to disinform the international
public opinion," said the spokesman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
