<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecution Closes Case Against Soldiers Charged With Treason </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LUSAKA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The prosecution Tuesday closed the six-
month-old case against 77 army soldiers who were charged with treason for
attempting to topple President Frederick Chiluba's elected government in a
military coup in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Director of Public Prosecution (DPP), Mukelebai Mukelebai, told trial
judge Japhet Banda in the Lusaka High Court that the prosecution has closed
its case after the 108th and last witness Tuesday testified in the court,
according to Zambia News Agency ZANA.
</P>
<P>
The defense welcomed the announcement and stated that they will start
making submission within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
And they will Wednesday lodge an application in the Lusaka High Court
for the release of six unnamed suspects who so far have not been implicated
in the case by any of the 108 prosecution witnesses.
</P>
<P>
Judge Banda allowed the defense's request, adding that he will also fix
the dates for hearing of submissions for both parties Thursday, said ZANA.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution have intended to call over 170 witnesses and only 108
of them have so far testified in one of the most complicated trials in the
Zambian history.
</P>
<P>
The treason trial started last June and initially 77 soldiers and
four civilians including two opposition leaders and a senior cadre of the
ruling Movement for Multi-party Democracy (MMD) were on trial for allegedly
taking part in the short-lived military coup on October 28, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Kenneth Kaunda, Zambian former president and leader of the country's
largest opposition party, the United National Independence Party (UNIP),
and his chief of security were charged with imprisonment of treason.
</P>
<P>
However, they were released as soon as the trial began after the state
entered a nolle prosequi, saying it was not "proper" to continue with the
case against them.
</P>
<P>
Dean Mung'omba, president of opposition Zambia Democratic Congress (ZDC)
 and Nakatindi Wina, former chairperson of women affairs of the MMD and
parliament member, were charged with treason together with the 77 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Mung'omba and Nakatindi Wina who were detained for about one year were
also discharged last month after the state entered a nolle prosequi since
no witnesses testified against them in the court.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the Lusaka High Court Monday ordered the state to
compensate the duo for wrongfully detaining them over treason charges,
arguing that there were no reasonable grounds for the state to have
commenced criminal proceedings against them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
