<HEADLINE> UN Commits to Objective of Humanitarian Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council on Tuesday said that it would commit itself to
the objective of the humanitarian program in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the Security Council was briefed on the
humanitarian situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Council President Celso Amorim of Brazil
said, "There was a general expression of commitment to the
objective of the humanitarian program and to the importance of
meeting the humanitarian meeds of Iraqi people among the Council
members."
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. diplomats, the Council this morning also
considered Iraq's request that the Untied Nations replace American
and British relief staff working in the country.
</P>
<P>
The diplomats said the U.N. Secretariat will make formal
response to Iraq's request this afternoon by stressing that it is
for the Untied Nations that decides who works for its program
and underline the responsibility for safeguarding the security of
all U.N. personnel.
</P>
<P>
Iraq on Monday officially asked the United Nations to replace
one American and 13 British humanitarian workers in the country on
grounds that it could not guarantee their safety because of
widespread anger caused by last month's air strikes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
