<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-05 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Deputy PM Calls On Iraq to Free Pows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Deputy Prime Minister
Abdel Aziz Dekheel Al-Dekheel Tuesday called on Iraq to fully
comply with U.N. resolutions and release all Kuwaiti Prisoners
of War (POW) detained since the 1990 Gulf Crisis.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference in Amman, Al-Dekheel said Kuwait will
continue to freeze its contacts with Iraq until Baghdad fully
comply with U.N. resolutions on Iraq adopted after the 1990 Gulf
Crisis, which was triggered by Iraq`s invasion of the Gulf
emirate.
</P>
<P>
But he said that Kuwait respects territorial integrity of Iraq
and supports humanitarian aid to the Iraqi people by the
international community.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has been blaming Iraq for keeping hundreds of Kuwaiti
nationals and POWs in detention after the Gulf War ended in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Al-Dekheel, also Kuwaiti Minister of State for Cabinet Affairs,
is in Amman for a one-day visit, which was aimed at ending the
eight-year strains in Kuwaiti-Jordanian relations.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Kuwait and Jordan were severed after the Gulf
war during which Jordan sided with Iraq together with a few other
Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
As to the reopening of Jordanian embassy in Kuwait, he said
that the proposed visit by Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdul Ilah
AL Hatib to Kuwait will help normalize relations between the two
countries, declining to give exact date of event.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Al-Dekheel met Jordanian Crown Prince and
the Regent Hassan Ibn Talal, and conveyed him a letter from his
Kuwaiti counterpart Saad Al-Abdullah Al-Salem Al-Sabah on
bilateral relations and regional developments.
</P>
<P>
Al-Dekheel, the highest ranking Kuwaiti official to visit Amman
since 1990, also had discussions with Hassan on efforts to
strengthen bilateral cooperation and matters of regional concern.
</P>
<P>
Analysts in Amman believed that Al-Dekheel`s visit to Amman
would help build up the momentum of normalizing bilateral ties
despite some opposition from the Kuwaiti public and parliament.
</P>
<P>
The Marathon rapprochement process between Kuwait and Jordan
started in May 1995, when Amman apparently distanced itself from
Baghdad, and called for political changes in Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
