<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Enhance Solid Mineral Industry in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Finance Minister Alhaji Usman said
here Tuesday that his government would allocate more funds to solid mineral
industry in a bid to diversify government revenue in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The minister said at a press briefing on the breakdown of the 1999
budget
that substantial allocation has been made in the budget for the airborne
geophysical survey of the country's solid mineral deposits to boost their
exploration and exploitation.
</P>
<P>
Funds have also been allocated for the procurement of three drilling
rigs and laboratory equipment in order to speed up sample drillings at
identified mineral deposit sites which would be carried out across the west
African country, he added.
</P>
<P>
Usman pointed out that the Nigerian Mining Corporation had been provided
with adequate funds for further exploration of minerals such as barytes,
kaolin, feldspar, talc, rock salt and gold.
</P>
<P>
The second phase of the Nigerian mineral appraisal and monetization
program project, currently at some 65 percent completion, will be pursued
vigorously this year, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
The rehabilitation of facilities in the various coal mines, the minister
said, will continue this year to prepare coal deposits for private
investment.
</P>
<P>
In his budget broadcast last Friday, Nigerian Head of State General
Abdulsalam Abubakar said that "If proper attention is given to the solid
minerals sector, it is capable of generating substantial revenue and
employment to supplement those derivable from the oil and non-oil sectors."
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the Nigerian government approved the new Solid Mineral Policy,
and revised laws and regulations to make the sector competitive while
generous incentives were provided for prospective investors.
</P>
<P>
On the briefing occasion, Usman also noted that the Nigerian government
had accorded priority to projects termed "vital" to the successful
implementation of the transition to civil rule program.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture received high priority in 1998 as a step toward achieving
self-sufficiency in food production, the minister said ,adding that the
tempo would be sustained this year.
</P>
<P>
Emphasis will be on the production of seeds and seedlings, soil
conservation, animal traction, tractors and agricultural equipment
rehabilitation as well as poverty alleviation projects, he stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Bombing Kills 100 Rebels in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The west African peace-keeping force in
Sierra Leone, ECOMOG, has killed more than 100 rebels during the bombing of
rebels' positions by Nigerian warplanes since Sunday, a report reaching
here said.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted an ECOMOG officer as saying Tuesday that Nigerian
Alpha jets have been bombing rebels in a mountain cave hide-out in Mankey,
near Hastings airport on the eastern outskirts of Sierra Leonean capital
Freetown, since Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We flattened the cave and killed more than 100 rebels on Sunday," said
the officer, based at the Jui military garrison for Nigerian and Ghanaian
ECOMOG troops near Hastings.
</P>
<P>
An ECOMOG spokesman said that Nigerian planes were also in action
around Lunsar, just north of Freetown, and that ECOMOG troops have retaken
total control of the nearby town of Port Loko and its surroundings.
The rebels are now in control of the whole northern part of Sierra Leone,
after intensive offensives in recent weeks, though their attempt to
infiltrate Freetown has been unsuccessful before the reinforced ECOMOG.
</P>
</TEXT>
