<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says no Back Down from Enforcing No-Fly Zones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Tuesday that it would not back down from enforcing no-fly zones
in Iraq in spite of a clash between U.S. and Iraqi warplanes.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to enforce the no-fly zones," White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters. "It's an important part
of our containment policy."
</P>
<P>
Lockhart's comment came after U.S. warplanes fired air-to-air
missiles at Iraqi aircraft earlier on Tuesday over the southern
no-fly zone in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Defense Department officials said one of the Iraqi planes was
believed to have crashed, but apparently not by the U.S.
missiles, after running out of fuel.
</P>
<P>
The American planes -- two Air Force F-15 strike aircraft and
two Navy F-14 fighters -- returned safely to the carrier Carl
Vinson where they took off for patrolling the no-fly zone.
</P>
<P>
The clash marked an escalation of tensions between Iraq and
the United States and Britain over enforcing the no-fly zones in
northern and southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said the no-fly zones were designed to limit Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein's ability to threaten his neighbors and
repress his people.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain airstruck Iraqi defense and
security installments in mid-December in an effort to reduce its
capability to develop weapons of mass destructions and
equipments that carry them.
</P>
<P>
Since the U.S.-British bombing of Iraq, there have been three
clashes taking place between the United States and Iraq. Iraq
claimed any patrol by Western warplanes would been seen as
violation of its air sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said Saddam was probably testing U.S. resolve on the
no-fly zones out of frustration at his isolated position.  
</P>
</TEXT>
