<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Peace Process Uncertain After Back on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The year of 1998 witnesses
two dramatic changes in the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
First, Israeli and Palestinian leaders signed a long
overdue land-for-peace agreement at the White House on October 23,
putting the peace process back on track after a 19-month stalemate.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, and more dramatically, the fragile right-wing
coalition of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu quickly
crumbled over the peace deal and the Knesset (parliament) decided
by an overwhelming vote to hold early elections, resulting in a
new stalemate in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the upcoming election would further delay
the implementation of the latest interim accord and help reshape
the whole peace process. No one can predict exactly at this
moment in what direction the process will move.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the interim accord, namely, the Wye River
Memorandum, is a result of the pragmatic strategy adopted by
Netanyahu and a greater mediating role played by Washington this
year.
</P>
<P>
Ideologically, Netanyahu might sympathize with those far
right-wingers who oppose the peacemaking with the Palestinians.
But politically, many people believe, he is a pragmatist who
realizes that his future lies in the peace process, which is
supported by more than three-fourths of the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
For the last two and a half years, Netanyahu has been torn
between his desire to get an agreement with the Palestinians and
the equally strong desire to retain the support of his right-wing
voters. He had done all he could to avoid making a choice, till he
could no longer find an excuse to play.
</P>
<P>
On its part, Washington tightened its screw on Netanyahu this
year because it had been painfully aware that the stalemate in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process has eroded American influence
across the Middle East, a point driven home by the lack of Arab
support in its standoffs with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
It put forward its own bridging proposal on the further Israeli
withdrawal from the West Bank in January, sent its Middle East
envoy Dennis Ross to shuttle between Israeli and Palestinian sides
frequently, and pushed them into direct negotiations which broke
down early last year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, top U.S. leaders held several separate or joint
talks with Israeli and Palestinian leaders, and issued sporadic
warnings to Netanyahu that Washington would reconsider its
mediating role if he refused to accept its proposal.
</P>
<P>
And in an unusual move in U.S. diplomatic history, President
Bill Clinton "locked" the two sides at the rustic and secluded
Wye Plantation for nine days in October and devoted scores of his
own time to the talks till an agreement was reached.
</P>
<P>
American officials later disclosed that although Netanyahu
had rebuffed U.S. ultimatums one after another, pressure from
Washington was in fact essential to dislodging the defiant prime
minister from a position of endless maneuvering short of a deal.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the peace accord has for a moment restored the
mutual-trust between Israel and the Palestinians, re-ignited the
enthusiasm among the two peoples for the peace process, and raised
hopes that the frozen Israeli-Syrian and Israeli-Lebanese talks
would also be resumed.
</P>
<P>
However, the trust, enthusiasm and hopes quickly evaporated
after the two sides were locked into a series of disputes over the
implementation of the agreement. One of the most serious disputes,
the one over the release of Palestinian prisoners, sparked weeks
of bloody clashes in occupied Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
And the peace process was stalled again as Netanyahu put the
agreement on hold in a futile attempt to save his cracking
government from falling apart. He charged the Palestinians of
failure to fulfill their obligations to fight terrorism, and set
new conditions for continuing the deal despite opposition from
Washington.
</P>
<P>
In fact, ever since he signed on the Wye River Memorandum,
Netanyahu has been caught between his hard-line coalition partners
rejecting the peace process and the center-left opposition who
wants to move it forward.
</P>
<P>
His government has been clinging to power only by a 61-59
majority in the 120-seat Knesset, since former foreign minister
David Levy resigned over disputes on the national budget in
January and all five Knesset members from his Gesher party quitted
the coalition.
</P>
<P>
By skillful maneuvering, Netanyahu has succeeded in pulling
together the brittle coalition in various crises. But after he
crossed a fateful political threshold at Wye, his coalition was
thrown into irreparable disarray.
</P>
<P>
Fewer than half of his ministers voted for the agreement when
it was approved in the cabinet, and it was only due to the support
of the opposition bloc that the accord was ratified by the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
After his attempt to broaden the coalition by bringing back
Levy and the Gesher Party failed and his call for a national unity
government with the Labor Party was rejected,
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu had no way to go but early elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
