<HEADLINE> Russia Denies Reports on Transferring Islands to Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Russian Deputy Foreign Minister
Grigory Karasin on Wednesday denied as "unfounded" Japanese
newspaper reports on a possible interim agreement on transferring
two South Kuril islands to Japan.
</P>
<P>
Karasin, who is in charge of drafting a peace treaty with
Japan, said such reports "are aimed at disrupting public
opinion," Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
Japanese mass media recently reported that Tokyo is
considering the possibility of concluding an interim agreement
with Moscow on the transfer of two of the four disputed South
Kuril islands to Japan and continuing talks on the territorial
status of the remaining two islands.
</P>
<P>
The four islands, known as the Northern Territories in Japan,
have stalled relations between Moscow and Tokyo for decades.
</P>
<P>
The long island chain was given to Japan in 1875 by Russia in
exchange for the northern half of Sakhalin Island. During the
Second World War, Russia retook the islands from Japan along with
the southern half of Sakhalin.
</P>
<P>
In 1951, Japan relinquished all claims to the islands but
later reversed its stance on the southern Kurils, stating that
these islands had always been Japanese possessions.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the governments of the two countries restarted
discussions over territorial sovereignty and fishing rights in
order to find a peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
At a regular press conference Wednesday, Russian Foreign
Ministry Spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin also denied the Japanese
reports as "sheer fabrication."
</P>
<P>
Moscow is guided by the "need to find a mutually-acceptable
solution to the territorial problem without affecting the two
countries' state interests, political positions and dignity,"
Rakhmanin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Rejects U.S. Demand Over Nuclear Requirements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 6 (Xinhua) -- India Wednesday rejected the
demand of the United States for it to spell out in concrete terms
its requirements for minimum nuclear deterrence, asserting that
there could be "no fixity" on it.
</P>
<P>
"This is entirely a matter of top secret assessment of the
country after taking into account possible threat perceptions," an
External Affairs Ministry spokesman said here.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Press Trust of India (PTI) Tuesday,
the U.S. ambassador to India Richard F. Celeste asked India to
specify in "concrete terms" its requirements of nuclear deterrence
so that it is not seen as an "open-ended threat" to its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. envoy also asked New Delhi to spell out how many
missile systems and warheads India needed to have such a
deterrent.
</P>
<P>
"In a fluctuating environment," the Indian spokesman said, "how
can you have a fixity? How can you determine the numbers or
range?"
</P>
<P>
He said India had made its position clear that in a situation
where there was no control over proliferation, nuclear deterrence
could not be fixed.
</P>
<P>
Informed circles here expressed their surprise over the revival
of the U.S. demand on the eve of a scheduled new round of talks
here later this month between the two sides on nuclear-related
issues.
</P>
<P>
Indian Minister of State for External Affairs Vasundhara Raje
also said on Wednesday that India had a "transparent" nuclear
policy and he ruled out any further clarification on it.
</P>
<P>
In the interview with PTI, Celeste said India's nuclear tests
last May "marked a kind of punctuation point" in relations between
Washington and New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
"Some expression of what India really wants and needs and
strives to achieve in a reasonably specific time, not specific in
numbers, but a range, is important to not only help the U.S.
understand but also specific neighbors to understand....So that
there isn't an open-ended threat," Celeste said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
