<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Preparations on Schedule for Swimming Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There was no problem in the budget, facilities and
preparations as a whole and things had been going on as
scheduled, said Ronnie Wong, secretary of the Hong Kong Amateur
Swimming Association and chairman of the championships' organizing
 committee.
</P>
<P>
Following an earlier promise of financial backing from the
Hong Kong Sports Development Board and the Hong Kong Tourist
Association, the world championships have now obtained a title
sponsor -- the China Travel Service (Holdings) HK Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Wong said more than 500 swimmers and 230 officials from 61
countries and regions had already been entered for the April 1-4
event in the Hong Kong Coliseum, Kowloon. This year's could be
the largest ever short-course world championships, Wong said,
compared with a field of some 700 swimmers at the Gothenburg,
Sweden championships four years ago.
</P>
<P>
A 25-meter portable pool, similar to the ones used in the two
previous world championships, will be installed in the fully
air-conditioned arena and a warm-up pool is scheduled to be
installed in March this year outside this largest sporting
facility in Hong Kong with some 8,500 seats.
</P>
<P>
Semi-finals for 50- and 100-meter events are to be added to
the competition schedule for the first time, according to a
revised program proved by the International Amateur Swimming
Federation (FINA), the sport's world governing body.
</P>
<P>
And Hong Kong will host the 13th FINA World Sports Medicine
Congress on April 5-7, immediately after the championships, Wong
said.
</P>
<P>
"We will try to act according to the principle of economics,
but we will do everything we can to make the event a success,"
Wong added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
