<HEADLINE> Spokesman Denies UNHRC Envoy Entering Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Ministry
spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi Wednesday denied a report on the
dispatch of an envoy of the U.N. Human Rights Commission (UNHRC)
to probe a chian of murders in Iran.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Republic of Iran does not allow any individual or
group to interfere in its domestic affairs, Asefi was quoted by
the Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) as saying.
</P>
<P>
An Iranian morning daily reported on Wednesday that an
Iranian woman representing the UNHRC had arrived in Tehran to
collect information on the recent spate of mysterious killings.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the government institutions in charge of
following up the crimes are strong enough to identify and arrest
those involved in the killings.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Intelligence Ministry announced on Tuesday night that
some of its agents were involved in the recent killings of
an opposition leader and several dissident writers.
</P>
<P>
Darious Forouhar, secretary general of the Iran Nation Party,
and his wife were stabbed to death at home in November and
three other Iranian dissident writers were also mysteriously
slain in Tehran in December.
</P>
<P>
Following the murders, the UNHRC planned to dispatch a
fact-finding team to Iran, but the proposal was rejected by
the Iranian authorities.
</P>
<P>
However, the morning daily Zan (Women) reported on Wednesday
that Elaheh Sharifpour, an Iranian woman in the UNHRC said
that she would come to Iran within two weeks to probe into
the killings.
</P>
<P>
But it is not clear whether Sharifpour will insist on coming
to Iran following the admittance of the Iranian Intelligence
Ministry about the involvement of its agents in the killings.
</P>
