<HEADLINE> Govt Takes Measures to Enhance HK's Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 6 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) said here Wednesday that
the government has taken a wide range of measures to enhance Hong
Kong's productive capacity and competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
Financial Secretary Donald Tsang said in a written reply in
the Legislative Council that in the light of developments in
other business centers in the region like Singapore, Taipei and
Shanghai, competition with Hong Kong must exist.
</P>
<P>
He noted that in the 1998/99 Budget he announced last February
and in the Chief Executive's Policy address last October, a wide
range of measures were set out to help lay the foundation for
economic recovery and maintain Hong Kong's position as a leading
business center in the world.
</P>
<P>
Tsang said the government has also introduced two specific
programs to ensure Hong ong remains alert to and on top of
competitive challenges.
</P>
<P>
These programs include the Services Promotion Program and the
Helping Business program.
</P>
<P>
The former looks systematically and comprehensively at the
services sector of the economy and identifies the action the
community needs to take to ensure Hong Kong remains the premier
services center in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The letter reviews ways the government can help the business
sector by cutting red tape, reducing cost of compliance,
identifying activities for transfer to the private sector, and
introducing new and improved services in support of the business
community. The overall objective is to ensure that Hong Kong
remains the best place in the world for business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
