<HEADLINE> Singapore Firms Turn Eyes on Beyond-Region Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Singapore firms have turned
their eyes to places beyond the region to look for new
opportunities and new markets, local TV Wednesday quoted the
country's top trade executive as saying.
</P>
<P>
Barry Desker, chief executive officer of Singapore's Trade
Development Board (TDB), made the assessment in an interview with
A.M Singapore. But he gave no exact figures.
</P>
<P>
Desker said companies have the regional crisis to thank for
their new venture into unknown markets.
</P>
<P>
"I think what is happening is that as easy opportunities in the
region have declined, our companies have begun to look for markets
beyond the region," Desker was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We have for example seafood traders who have found excellent
opportunities in markets like Eastern Africa, Bangladesh, India,
which they never explored previously," he said.
</P>
<P>
Desker said the TDB will focus on developing Singapore as a
leading trade exhibition hub and as a shipping and logistics
center.
</P>
<P>
He affirmed that marketing services will also be developed in
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The TDB plays a key role in charting the course for Singapore's
trade.
</P>
<P>
Export is Singapore's key locomotive of economic growth.
Singapore's principal markets for export include the U.S.,
Malaysia, Japan, Hong Kong, Britain and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
As one of its measures to tide over the current economic
recession, the Singapore government is making efforts to help
local companies explore and penetrate new markets to offset the
fall in regional demand.
</P>
<P>
In the second half of 1998, Singapore organized dozens of
missions to Eastern Europe, Africa, Latin America, the Middle East
and South Asia in a bid to explore markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
