<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Needs to Repay 4.7 Billion Dollars in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Iran needs to repay 4.7 billion
U.S. dollars of its foreign debts in the new Iranian calendar year
to start March 21, the Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA)
reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting a report from the Central Bank of Iran, IRNA said that
the country's total due debts in the current Iranian year was 3.76
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The total foreign debts, comprising short-term, medium-term and
long-term debts, stood at 11.9 billion dollars by the end of the
first half of this year, some 168 million dollars
less than that at the end of the past Iranian year.
</P>
<P>
The report put the total debts and foreign undertakings of the
country at 22.4 billion dollars by the end of the first half of
the current year, which also include probable undertakings and
future interests.
</P>
<P>
Iran's foreign debts dropped from 22.7 billion dollars in
March 1995 to 12.1 billion dollars in March 1998, IRNA said.
</P>
<P>
Iran's oil incomes declined by half this year as a result of
oil price slump.
</P>
<P>
A report by Iranian Customs said recently that the country only
earned 2.1 billion dollars from non-oil exports during the first
nine months of the current year, a 11.3 percent drop from the same
period of the last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iran's imports during the period stood at 11.4
billion dollars, a 11 percent decrease from the corresponding
period last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
