<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda's Capital Has Fewer Road Accidents in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- About 4,630 road accidents were
recorded in Uganda's capital city of Kampala in the year 1998, a five
percent decrease from the previous year, a senior police officer told
Xinhua Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
 In an interview with Xinhua Wednesday morning, Grace Turyagumanawe,
police commander in charge of traffic safety in Kampala Region, said: "
Accidents have decreased over the years.
They were 8,068 in 1995 and 5,566 in 1996. Pedestrians still suffer most in
all these cases."
</P>
<P>
In the year 1998, 318 people, most of them pedestrians, were killed in
road accidents and 2,577 injured, with altogether 6,537 vehicles involved.
</P>
<P>
Some 361 pedal cyclists were involved in accidents because there is no
bicycle lane on the roads, he said.
</P>
<P>
Among the key causes of accidents, the police commander listed speeding,
 drunk driving, careless pedestrians as well as using forged driving
permits.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the police scrutinized 6,576 driving licenses and found that
6,332 were forged. The police authorities have taken effective measures
against use of forged driving permits over the years and as a result, road
accidents reduced dramatically.
</P>
<P>
Turyagumanawe, who was recently posted to police headquarters as an
assistant commissioner in charge of traffic and road safety, said that laws
must be put in place to deal with mobile phone usage while driving and
safety belt use to curb accidents.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
