<HEADLINE> Shahak Under Fire after Aiming at Premiership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Former army chief Amnon
Lipkin-Shahak came under immediate fire Wednesday from both the
ruling Likud and the opposition Labor Party after he criticized
the two main parties while declaring his candidacy in the coming
elections.
</P>
<P>
Members of the two parties said Shahak did not provide
anything new when he kicked off his election campaign and made
public his platform at a nationally broadcast news conference in
Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
Likud officials also blamed him for launching a "personal
attack" against Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and described
him as a leftist rather than a centrist he has claimed.
</P>
<P>
Firing his first shot, Shahak said Netanyahu has failed to
bring "peace with security" to Israel as he promised before being
elected as prime minister in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"Today there is no peace, no security. The economic situation
is bad and the social situation is sad," the popular former chief
of staff said. "Netanyahu is dangerous to Israel, Netanyahu must
go."
</P>
<P>
As head of a new centrist party, Shahak said neither the Likud
nor the Labor can represent the Israeli public, adding that a new
leadership is needed for a country which is divided over social,
religious issues as well as peacemaking with Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
While acknowledging as a political novice, Shahak stressed
that he had been entrusted by slain Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin
as a representative to negotiate peace with the Palestinians and
Syrians.
</P>
<P>
A Palestinian state can not be established until a permanent
agreement has been reached, he said, adding that a solution to
Israel's withdrawal from south Lebanon can be found only through
negotiations with Damascus.
</P>
<P>
His party is expected to take votes away from all parties in
the elections set on May 17, but mainly from the Labor, which is
led by another former chief of staff Ehud Barak, also a protege
of Rabin.
</P>
<P>
Shahak has discussed coordination in the elections with Likud
defector Dan Meridor, who is also forming a centrist party, but
failed to reach agreement on who should be the head of a merged
list. 
</P>
</TEXT>
