<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Millions of Indian Babies Threatened With Anemia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Millions of babies born every
day in India were at the risk of deformity and other
life-threatening diseases even before their birth due to maternal
anemia, an Indian expert warned Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The risk arose as maternal anemia led to malsecretion of
several important hormones, said N. Kochupillai, head of
Department of Endocrinology and Metabolism at the All-India
Institute of Medical Sciences.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that this condition was hardly diagnosed or
treated in the country due to inadequate professional expertise
and lack of reliable and cost-effective testing methods, and most
of the testing kits had been imported.
</P>
<P>
According to Kochupillai, the disease could be prevented by
hormone replacement therapy.
</P>
<P>
Highlighting the importance of hormone replacement therapy in
fighting several diseases, he said deficiency of thyroid hormone
at birth, which causes mental retardation in children, was 10-20
times higher in many parts of the country than in other countries.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
