<HEADLINE> Malaysian King Praises Sino-Malaysian Relationship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Supreme Head of
State Tuanku Ja'afar said here Wednesday that the bilateral ties
in the political, economic, military and cultural fields between
Malaysia and China enjoyed rapid development in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The ruling parties of the two countries have established ties,
people-to-people exchanges have been increasing steadily and
tourism between the two countries is also flourishing, the king
said during a farewell call by outgoing Chinese Ambassador Qian
Jinchang at the King's Palace here.
</P>
<P>
Tuanku Ja'afar said the economic and trade cooperation between
the two countries has bright prospects.
</P>
<P>
The past five years when Qian served here as the Chinese
ambassador was a period witnessing the great development of the
relations between Malaysia and China, he said, citing frequent
exchange of visits by the top leaders of the two countries,
including three visits by Chinese President Jiang Zemin to
Malaysia and his own visit to China.
</P>
<P>
The king also noted the smooth development of the relations
between the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and
China, and praised China for its role at the informal meeting
among East Asian leaders in Hanoi, Vietnam, last month.
</P>
<P>
Tuanku Ja'afar said Malaysia and China are close neighbors and
the friendship between the two countries and the two peoples
should pass on from generation to generation, and that the
ASEAN-China relationship should also be further strengthened.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian king also spoke highly of the capability of the
Chinese leaders to keep China away from being affected by the
financial crisis in East Asia. 
