<HEADLINE> Turkish PM Designate Returns Mandate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister designate
Yalim Erez announced here Tuesday that he had returned the mandate
for the formation of the 56th government to President Suleyman
Demirel.
</P>
<P>
Erez, the incumbent industry and trade minister, made the
announcement after a 30-minute-long talk with Demirel at the
presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
Demirel had picked up Erez, an independent lawmaker, to form
the government late last December after the previous prime
minister designate and Democratic Left Party (DSP) leader Bulent
Ecevit failed to secure a majority in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Erez's decision to return the mandate came two days after the
True Path Party (DYP) leader Tansu Ciller lent a sudden support
for a proposal of a DSP minority government led by Ecevit, a
U-turn stance from last December, when she opposed the proposal of
a coalition of DSP, DYP and the Motherland Party.
</P>
<P>
Motherland Party leader Mesut Yilmaz and Ecevit had also called
on Erez to return his mandate to Demirel, showing that they were
satisfied with Ciller's support to the proposal of the DSP
minority government.
</P>
<P>
Erez resigned as industry and trade minister in an earlier
coalition between Ciller's DYP and pro-Islamic Welfare Party in
April 1997, two months after the military forces warned the
government to strictly act on the secular constitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
