<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE's GDP Falls 5.5 Percent on Oil Slump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The gross domestic product
(GDP) of the United Arab Emirates declined 5.5 percent last year
due to the fall in oil prices, Planning Minister Sheikh Ahmed
Al-Mualla announced on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The GDP declined to 46.4 billion U.S. dollars in 1998 from 49.2
billion dollars in 1997, according to a report on the country's
economic performance in 1998 and projections for this year.
</P>
<P>
The minister, however, added that the non-oil GDP continued to
increase from 34.7 billion dollars in 1997 to 36.3 billion dollars
last year.
</P>
<P>
The GDP is expected to recover to 48.1 billion dollars this
year because of a likely increase in non-oil GDP to 37.4 billion
dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister attributed the growth in non-oil GDP to the
government's plan to diversify revenue sources through industrial
activities.
</P>
<P>
The statement pointed out that commercial activities and
wholesale and retail trade contributed 15.4 percent of the total
GDP in 1998 with the private sector playing the main role in this
field.
</P>
<P>
The real estate sector made up 13.7 percent of the GDP while
construction accounted for 12.2 percent, followed by
transportation, storage and telecommunications sector with 9.2
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
