<HEADLINE> Congolese Rebel Leader Dismisses Capturing More Towns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NAIROBII, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD)
 engaged in a five-month rebellion against President Laurent Desire Kabila
has dismissed claims by Congolese government and its allies that they
recaptured key towns in the east and north of the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters in the Rwandan capital Kigali, the RCD C hairman,
Ernest Wamba dia Wamba, said Tuesday that the situation is calm on the
battlefield, and that the rebels are still in control of the towns of Moba,
Fizi, Nyunzu and Kabalo, the Rwanda News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
 He also denied reports from Kinshasa alleging that 1,000 Congolese
rebels were killed in Moba, and that Fizi had been bombed.
</P>
<P>
''They never took Moba, they did not kill one thousand as they claimed,
Fizi was never bombed,'' Wamba told journalists.
</P>
<P>
 Wamba and other rebel leaders including commander Jean
Pierre Ondekane were in stop-over in Kigali, coming from Kampala where they
held talks with Ugandan officials at the week-end.
</P>
<P>
According to Wamba, the visit to both capitals of their two major
backers was in the framework of regular tripartite consultations.
</P>
<P>
 He said that they need to get more on the experience
of the leadership in both countries about the liberation struggle.
</P>
<P>
This visit occurred amidst wide-spread reports that the rebel movement
is rocked with internal rifts, and that senior officials are engaged in a
bitter rivalry.
</P>
<P>
The RCD chairman, however, played down divisions in the movement, by
saying that the rebellion is still strong and united.
</P>
<P>
He blamed the so-called divisions on confusing statements made recently
by some members which led to misinterpretations which made people believe
that the movement was breaking away.
</P>
<P>
He also dismissed allegations that the RCD is pitted
against newly-formed Congolese Liberation Movement (MLC) of millionaire
businessman, Jean Pierre Bemba allegedly supported by Uganda.
</P>
<P>
''We are a rally for democracy which means that we rally political
formations, personalities of the civil society,'' Wamba indicated, saying
that contacts have already been engaged with Bemba with the objective of
finding out a precise relationship p of collaboration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
