<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Nepal Striving to Attract Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Nepalese government has
taken a number of measures to attract foreign direct investment in
the country since 1992 when the economic liberalization program
was launched.
</P>
<P>
Historically, private foreign investment had not been very
important in Nepal's growth strategy, and until before the
restoration of democracy in the country in 1990, only 86 foreign
investment projects had been approved with total foreign capital
investment of 5.9 billion rupees, according to the Spotlight, an
English weekly.
</P>
<P>
But the government's attitude has changed significantly since
the economic liberalization program started in 1992. That very
year, the Foreign Investment and One Window Policy, the Foreign
Investment and Technology Transfer Act and the Industrial
Enterprise Act were adopted, offering a number of incentives to
foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
These include permission to set up 100 percent foreign-owned
enterprises in medium and large-scale industries with a few
exceptions, allowing repatriation by foreigners investing in
convertible currencies, legal provision to stop double taxation
for foreigners, concessions in taxes and provision of special
facilities with respect to land, water and electricity.
</P>
<P>
Besides, a One Window Committee was established to provide all
facilities for the establishment, expansion and modernization of
industries and the license system was abolished for establishing
industries except in defense, public health and environment
sectors.
</P>
<P>
"Now the government intends to be a little government, not big
government, little bureaucracy, not big bureaucracy, little
regulatory function, not big regulatory function. This is the main
motto of the industrial policy," Govind Prasad Kusum, joint
secretary at the Ministry of Industry, told Xinhua in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
He said that since the initiative of economic diplomacy was
launched in June 1996, Nepal's foreign missions have been doing
their best within given resources to promote foreign investment in
the country.
</P>
<P>
By 1998, 470 foreign investment projects have been approved
with a total foreign direct investment of 12.71 billion rupees, he
said, adding that India is the biggest investor in Nepal followed
by the United States, Japan and China.
</P>
<P>
He noted that 205 projects have begun operation and 55 are
under construction.
</P>
<P>
Nepal has to enhance the foreign direct investment because many
priority sectors remain untouched, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We like to welcome all foreign investors just to invest their
resources, their capital in those sectors especially hydropower,
infrastructure development, agro-based industries, mining," he
added. "These are our potential areas where foreign direct
investment can be utilized properly."
</P>
<P>
Compared with other countries in the region, he said, Nepal has
enough opportunities and facilities for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
He said Nepal has many more sectors open to foreigners and
there is no market problem here. "India is there, China is there,"
he explained.
</P>
<P>
"Now the areas where foreign investors can contribute are more
attractive to them, say, hydropower. We have enough water," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that a company investing in hydropower in Nepal is
entitled to sell the electricity wherever it likes.
</P>
<P>
"Next, there is agro-based industries, we have many
potentialities, because being an agricultural country, we have
many agricultural products," he said.
</P>
<P>
Even a single agricultural product like tea has good market in
India, in other South Asian countries and European countries as
well, he said.
</P>
<P>
Other sectors like tourism, infrastructure and mining also
offer good opportunities, he said.
</P>
<P>
Nepal has enough mines including even petroleum, he said,
adding that last month a U.S. company signed an agreement with
Nepal to explore gas in the country.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that some bottlenecks like poor coordination
and lack of proper transportation and electricity deter the flow
of more foreign direct investment in the country.
</P>
<P>
But the government is trying its best to create a conducive
environment for investors, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
