<HEADLINE> Chang Replaces Sampras in Colonial Classic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Former world No. 2 and
three-time Colonial Classic title-holder, Michael Chang has taken
up his option as first alternate for the Kooyong event in
Australia following the withdrawal of Pete Sampras last weekend.
</P>
<P>
Chang, now ranked 29th, was beaten by Australian Scott Draper
in the second round of the Australian Hardcourt Championships in
Australia's port city of Adelaide 6-3, 7-6 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 1989 French open champion won the Colonial title in three
successive years - 1995, 1996 and 1997. He will join Andre
Agassi, Tim Henman, Yevgeny Kafelnikov, Goran Ivanisevic, Petr
Korda, Mark Philippoussis and Thomas Enqvist in the eight-man
field.
</P>
<P>
"We are pleased to have Michael join us for our tenth
anniversary event. He has been a long time supporter of the
Colonial Classic and always give 100 per cent in his matches,"
tournament director Colin Stubs told the Australian Associated
Press.
</P>
<P>
All players will play three matches over four days starting
next Monday. 
