<HEADLINE> Egypt Says Arabs Agree to Hold Meeting of FMs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said here on Wednesday that Arab countries "fully agree on
holding the consultative meeting" of their foreign ministers on
January 24.
</P>
<P>
"The Arab League is not awaiting written responses from its
members because they all agree on its holding, thus its timing is
not in question," Moussa told reporters after a meeting with Arab
League chief Esmat Abdel-Meguid.
</P>
<P>
Arab countries decided initially to convene a foreign ministers
meeting a week ago to discuss a Yemeni call for an urgent Arab
summit on the situation in the Arab world after U.S.-British
military strikes against Iraq last month.
</P>
<P>
Requested by Kuwait, Saudi Arabia and other Gulf countries, the
meeting was put off to January 24 for better preparation and
consultations.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that he examined with Abdel-Meguid preparations for
the planned foreign ministers' meeting, briefing the Arab League
chief on the ongoing contacts for the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Moussa and his counterparts of Oman, Saudi Arabia, Syria and
Yemen met Saturday in Egypt in a bid to reach an agreement among
Arab countries on issues to be raised at the upcoming foreign
ministers meeting.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on prospects for another five-way consultation on
the proposed meeting, Moussa said that it depends on whether the
ministers have time for such a gathering.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is approaching and several ministers have busy
schedules, he said. But he added that consultations and contacts
are continuing on various levels.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid said his meeting with Moussa came as part of the
consultations with Egypt on the latest Arab coordination and the
preparations for the foreign ministers consultative meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Arab meeting will be held as scheduled and there is no
intention to postpone it once again, he said.
</P>
<P>
The issue of whether an Arab summit is to be held will be left
to the Arab leaders to decide in line with the results of the
January 24 meeting, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
