<HEADLINE> HK Welcomes Int'l Cooperation in Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 6 (Xinhua) -- In line with the policy to
maintain a free and open market, Hong Kong welcomes international
participation in infrastructure development, a senior official of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) said here W
ednesday.
</P>
<P>
Financial Secretary Donald Tsang said at an international
meeting that a "significant number of international companies
have been awarded construction or consulting contracts in Hong
Kong."
</P>
<P>
Tsang was speaking at the opening ceremony of Senior
Official-level Meeting of the Third Ministers' Forum on
Infrastructure Development in Asia Pacific Region.
</P>
<P>
"Heavy capital investment and keen competition for
international financing means that this Forum, in particular,
provides an excellent opportunity to discuss and encourage
complementary development in the Asia Pacific context," Tsang
said.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the ceremony, Secretary for Works Kwong
Hon-sang said Hong Kong has excellent professionals who have
built up experience in working with multi-disciplinary and
multi-national teams for its infrastructure development.
</P>
<P>
Kwong said Hong Kong's infrastructure development was
characterized by the need to cater for a fast growing population
and the rapid expansion of the city's economic activities.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting will identify issues of common interest
to the 14 participating countries and regions for in-depth
discussions at the Ministers' Forum scheduled for May.
</P>
<P>
The issues to be addressed at the meeting will include the use
of information technology for infrastructure development, high
density living in an urban environment, and harmony of
infrastructure and environment.
</P>
<P>
Participants of the meeting also came from Australia, Brunei,
Chile, China, Indonesia, Japan, Papua New Guinea, Republic of
Korea, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
