<HEADLINE> Labor Body's Fresh Ultimatum to Nigerian Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LAGOS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria Labor Congress (NLC) has given the
Nigerian government a fresh 14-day ultimatum to resume talks on the issues
of the oil price hike and slash in approved minimum wages.
</P>
<P>
The renewed ultimatum was issued at a meeting held here Tuesday of the
13-member NLC caretaker committee and representatives of the 29 industrial
unions in the country, This Day newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting took place after Nigerian Head of State General Abdulsalami
Abubakar announced in his 1999 budget broadcast last Friday that "the
government is encouraging the petroleum marketers to enter into discussion
with consumers."
</P>
<P>
NLC caretaker committee Chairman Godwin Wodwin told reporters after the
meeting that labor is not comfortable with the head of state's directive
when the government is aware that no such group exists.
</P>
<P>
On the recent slash in the minimum wages for civil servants, he
disclosed that the 5,200-Naira (about 60.5 U.S. Dollars) minimum monthly
pay recently approved for civil servants would not be compromised by the
NLC.
</P>
<P>
On December 23 last year, the NLC issued a 12-day ultimatum to the
government to revert to the old pump price of fuel which was increased to
25 Naira (about 0.29 Dollars) from 11 Naira per liter.
</P>
<P>
The government reacted swiftly by summoning a meeting with labor
leaders and succeeded in persuading them to suspend the ultimatum, leading
to the setting up of two different committees to handle the issues of fuel
price hike and the slash in minimum wages.
</P>
<P>
Government officials last week met representatives of the two
committees to resolve the two controversial issues but could not reach a
compromise as both parties failed to shift grounds on their positions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
