<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Speaker Hails Arrest of Serial Murders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 6 (Xinhua) -- A leading Iranian conservative on
Wednesday hailed the Intelligence Ministry for arresting some of
its agents in connection with the killing Iranian dissidents and
intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
Majlis (parliament) speaker Ali Akbar Nateq Nouri said at the
Majlis session that "national sovereignty and security, as well as
the interests of the system and people, is the principle."
</P>
<P>
"The system will severely encounter any individual or group
that tries to violate this principle," he said, quoted by the
Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The Intelligence Ministry on Tuesday night expressed regret
that a few of its own "devious colleagues" were involved in a
series of mysterious political killings in the country.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the ministry said that it has succeeded in
breaking the criminal network and would bring them to justice.
But it did not say how many suspects were arrested.
</P>
<P>
Darius Forouhar, secretary general of the Iran Nation Party and
a prominent opposition leader, and his wife were stabbed to death
at home in November and several dissident writers were also
mysteriously slain in Tehran in December.
</P>
<P>
The killings shocked the public as the moderates, led by
President Mohammed Khatami, and the hard-line conservatives, who
control most of the powers in the Islamic regime, were engaged in
a bitter power struggles.
</P>
<P>
Khatami ordered the ministries of interior and intelligence to
form a special committee to probe into the cases, which led to the
discovery of the perpetrators inside the government establishment.
</P>
<P>
The conservative speaker, however, cautioned that the issue "is
more complicated than it seems." "If we follow up the news
transmitted by foreign news agencies and radio stations these
days, we will realize that our enemies are following other
objectives," he said without elaboration.
</P>
<P>
Some conservatives have blamed foreign enemies for the
murders. The speaker noted that it was not easy to say whether
foreign hands were behind these events, "it is not easy to answer
this question and it is not easy to rule it out either." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Satisfied With Peso's Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said here Wednesday that the Philippine peso would settle
at 38-39 against the U.S. dollar this year.
</P>
<P>
The peso hit an eight-month intra-day high of 37.96 to the
dollar and closed at 38.00 Tuesday, the strongest level since
reaching 37.97 to the greenback on April 12, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The currency continued to show its strength Wednesday and was
traded at 38.10 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
"When I assumed office (at the end of June), the rate was 45
pesos to a dollar. Now it's 38 pesos to a dollar. So this is a big
improvement," Estrada said in an interview with reporters.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that any further gain of the peso would affect
the country's exports.
</P>
<P>
"Well, I think 38-39 pesos will be just enough to stabilize the
peso, because if it drops lower than 38 pesos the exporters would
be adversely affected," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson attributed the
peso's appreciation to investor confidence in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
"It's a combination of factors, but the most important thing is
that the confidence of investors is returning and that speculation
is dying down," Singson said.
</P>
<P>
Singson also said the peso is likely to be stable at its
present rate this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
