<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Takes Measures to Keep Goods Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's Pricing Committee has
issued a circular on guidelines to manage and maintain stable
prices of goods while the value added tax (VAT) Law is in force,
Vietnam News Agency (VNA) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's VAT Law began in force on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
In the circular, the Vietnamese government asks ministries,
ministerial-level agencies, centrally-run agencies, and provincial
and municipal people's committees to re-examine the production
cost and set suitable selling prices of goods, strengthen the
management of production, transport and service costs, inspect
price tags and actual sale prices and monitor the fluctuation of
prices on the market with a view to maintaining stable prices,
especially during the days before the traditional lunar new year
festival (the Spring Festival).
</P>
<P>
The circular of the Vietnamese government calls on all
businesses to maintain the prices of goods and services at the
level in late 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government also asks ministries, branches and
localities to re-calculate the supply-demand balance of
commodities under their management in order to avoid unexpected
price hikes.
</P>
<P>
According to Deputy General Director of Vietnam's Taxation
Department Nguyen Van Dau, the prices of goods on the market
basically remained stable during the first four days of applying
VAT. The prices of some essential goods and services that are
under state management such as electricity, petroleum, rice, post
and telecommunications and transport are unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
