<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Machinery Industry Expected To Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 6 (Xinhua) -- China's machinery industry is
scheduled to grow by 8 percent in 1999, with the sector's net
profits expected to hit 10 billion yuan (1.2 billion US dollars),
according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
Sun Changji, deputy director of the State Administration of
the Machinery Industry, said that the country's machinery
industry kept growing in 1998, in spite of the negative impact of
the Asian financial, when addressing a national conference on
China's machinery industry which opened in Shanghai today.
</P>
<P>
He said that the sector's total output value increased by 3.1
percent to 451 billion yuan in the first 11 months of last year.
However, the sector's pre-tax profits plunged by 39.27 percent
on a year-on-year basis, standing at 5.6 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Many Chinese machinery enterprises suffered losses in 1998,
accounting for more than half of the country's total. The total
losses were estimated at 13.6 billion yuan, up nearly 20 percent
from the same period of the previous year, because of increasing
numbers of unsold products.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Chinese-made machinery products accounted for
65 percent of the share of the China market in 1998, however,
painstaking efforts should be made to expand the rural market for
Chinese machinery manufacturers and to develop more products to
meet the needs of Chinese consumers.
</P>
<P>
He said that a number of Chinese manufacturers of machinery
tools, food packaging and mining machinery were forced to reduce
their production in 1998, because of changes in China's foreign
trade policies and the financial crisis among Southeast Asian
states.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
