<HEADLINE> Share Prices Soar on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Share prices soared up on the
Singapore Stock Market Wednesday as foreign funds tricked in after
returning from the holidays.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) surged up 78.73 points
to 1,464.97 after an active session.
</P>
<P>
The total turnover ran up to 450.27 million units worth 657.76
million Singapore dollars (392.22 million U.S. dollars). Gainers
outstripped losers by 308 to 17 while 95 counters remained
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
CK Tang, a retailer, was the most favorite stock of the day
with a volume of 24.65 million units. SemCorp was the second most
heavily traded share with a turnover of 19.64 million units. ERL,
an electronics company whose takeover by U.S. computer distributor
Ingram Micro has helped to spark speculation about possible
takeover in other segments, was next with 17.02 million counters
changing hands.
</P>
<P>
F &AMP; N headed ascents of the day with a jump of 85 cents to 5.80
Singapore dollars. It was followed by OCBC F that surged up 80
cents to 12.00 Singapore dollars. Creative 50 climbed 70 cents to
finish at 24.80 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, DBS F was the biggest losers of the day with a
drop of 10 cents to 15.00 Singapore dollars. StarCru was next
retreating eight cents to 2.03 U.S. dollars. ITE Elec w00 sank
four cents to end at 0.09 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the market was boosted by foreign buying after
foreign funds returned from their holidays.
</P>
<P>
The rumors that OCBC and OUB, both among the Big Four Banks in
Singapore, would be announcing merger fueled buying of their
shares. But banks said they were not aware of such an
announcement.
</P>
<P>
Dealers also contributed today's strong hike to Wall Street's
overnight rally that encouraged U.S. and U.K. funds to get a
little more active.
</P>
<P>
In addition, they noted foreign funds traditionally set up
markets for rally at beginning of a year. 
</P>
