<HEADLINE> UK Says Iraqi Safety Claims "Bogus" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook Wednesday rejected Iraq's suggestion of popular unrest
threatening the safety of British aid workers in Iraq after the
U.S. and British air strikes against Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
"The suggestion that popular unrest and feeling is going to
pose a risk to British or any other UN workers is a wholly bogus
argument," Cook told BBC Radio.
</P>
<P>
Iraq said it feared for the safety of the Britons and
Americans who are working for the United Nations now in Iraq
because of "deep popular anger" after the air strikes on Iraq by
Britain and the Unites States, which had damaged schools,
hospitals, factories and other civilian targets.
</P>
<P>
"Let us remember these are humanitarian workers. On the whole,
what they do is overwhelmingly popular with the Iraqi people,"
Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Asked if he would contemplate pulling the British workers out
of Iraq, he said: "The safety of British citizens is always of
paramount concern."
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Secretary welcomed the outcome of the United
Nations meeting in New York, which rejected Baghdad's request to
replace British and U.S. humanitarian staff. 
</P>
