<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State-Owned Enterprise Reform Tops Chinese Officials' Concerns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The reform of State-owned
enterprises is the main concern of top Chinese officials in 1999,
according to a survey conducted by the Party School of the
Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC).
</P>
<P>
The random survey sent out 125 questionnaires and 121 were
returned. The respondents are mainly government and Party
officials at the city and prefectural level across the country.
</P>
<P>
The questionnaire listed 12 hot issues of the 1999 reform, and
respondents were required to arrange them in accordance with
their importance.
</P>
<P>
Results show that 40.5 percent of those surveyed regard the
reform of state-owned enterprises as the primary issue of the
1999 reform, followed by institutional restructuring, political
reform and housing reform.
</P>
<P>
The reforms of the social medicare, distribution system and
household register management, however, were not the main choices.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, officials in eastern and central parts of
the country showed greater concern about the reform of
state-owned enterprises than institutional reform. Officials from
western China took an opposite view.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 50.1 percent of those surveyed from the
west targeted institutional restructuring as the top concern, as
against 30.9 percent who chose the state-owned enterprise reform.
</P>
<P>
As for factors affecting the state-owned enterprise reform,
34.7 percent of officials regarded the change of governmental
administrative functions as the most important, followed by
property reform and internal management of enterprises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
