<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Economy Records 2.36 Percent Growth in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LAGOS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's economy recorded 2.36 percent
growth in 1998, down from 3.77 percent in 1997, Finance Minister
Ismaila Usman has said.
</P>
<P>
Briefing reporters Tuesday in Nigerian capital Abuja on the 1999 budget,
 the minister said the government recorded a deficit of 57 billion Naira
(one U.S. Dollar equals to 86 Naira) last year, compared with a projected
surplus of one billion Naira.
</P>
<P>
The government had projected an oil price of 17 Dollars a barrel in its
1998 budget, but the average price in the past year is only around 12
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The slump in the oil price has caused a great financial difficulty for
the government, which depends on oil export for more than 80 percent of its
budgetary income and above 90 percent of its hard currency earning.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the minister said the country earned only 6.8 billion
Dollars from oil export in 1998, 76 percent down from the 12 billion
Dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
In fact, he said, the performance of the economy in 1998 represented a
setback in almost every index compared with that of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate, which was expected to decline to six percent in
1998, rose to 9.8 percent instead, compared with 8.5 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign reserve declined from 7.7 billion Dollars in 1997
to 7.1 billion Dollars by December 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
