<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The shares at the Seoul stock
market Wednesday surged 13.81 points, closing at 612.36, the
highest level since October, 1997.
</P>
<P>
A total of 260.3 million shares valued at 2.6 trillion won
(some 2.2 billion U.S. dollars) changed hands. Winners
outnumbered losers at 646 against 200 while 39 others remained
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday is the sixth day in a row that the South Korean
stocks have rallied.
</P>
<P>
Stock analysts said the share market surged as small investors
and foreign players engaged in active buying with the local
currency strengthening against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the stock market has rallied based on anticipation
of possible upgrading of South Korea's credit ratings by
international rating organizations.
</P>
<P>
The strength of the won against the greenback also helped
improve investor sentiment.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean won appreciated at 1,159 against the
greenback from the previous day's 1,167.
</P>
<P>
The market rallied strongly, supported by ample liquidity as
investors maintained their position of buying stocks, said a
dealer.
</P>
<P>
He said investment trust companies began to purchase
shares,especially blue-chip stocks as part of their efforts to
manage their newly-created stock-invested funds.
</P>
<P>
The dealer also predicted that the Seoul stock market will
soon rise to 640-650 level if the current bullish sentiment
continues. 
