<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Domestic Debt, Education Priority in Nigeria's 1999 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LAGOS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has given top
priority of its 1999 budget to domestic debt service and education,
according to breakdown of the budget carried on major newspapers here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The breakdown, given by Finance Minister Ismaila Usman in Nigerian
capital Abuja Tuesday, shows that about 39 billion Naira (one U.S. Dollar
equals to 86 Naira) would be spent on domestic debt service, accounting for
13 percent of the total budgetary spending of 300 billion Naira.
</P>
<P>
For the second year, education is given the second largest share of 27.
7 billion Naira, or 9.2 percent of the total vote.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the government announced a special refurbishing grant of 1.4
billion Naira to 17 chosen universities, education colleges as well as the
Nigeria Defense Academy.
</P>
<P>
The third biggest cake goes to defense, which will gulp nearly 26
billion Naira, or 8.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The police will receive 21 billion Naira, or seven percent of the
budget.
</P>
<P>
The agriculture sector is given 7.5 billion Naira, or a share of 2.5
percent, while 13.7 billion Naira, or 4.6 percent, is allocated to the
health sector.
</P>
<P>
The Independent National Electoral Commission, which is in harge of the
country's transition to civil rule program, is granted 1.2 billion Naira.
</P>
<P>
The government announced a modest investment of one billion Naira in
the power sector, which, according to the minister, will be mainly spent on
rural electrification projects.
</P>
<P>
Due to the slump in the international oil price, Nigeria, which depends
more than 80 percent of its budgetary income on crude oil export, is
expecting a deficit of 34.1 billion Naira in 1999, representing 1.05
percent of its projected gross domestic product. 
</P>
</TEXT>
