<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Chief to Visit Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LAGOS, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The IMD Managing Director will lead a 19-
man team to visit Nigeria in mid-January to finalize discussions on the
Staff Maintained Program (SMP) which is a pre-condition to negotiating the
Medium Term Economic Strategy (MTES) for Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
In his briefing of the breakdown of the 1999 budget held Tuesday in
capital Abuja, Nigerian Finance Minister Mallam Usman said Nigeria and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) had agreed on virtually all the
conditions set for the commencement of the MTES, This Day reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
While in the country, the IMF team will discuss with the Nigerian
government on the expanded version of the MTES which involves instituting
major market based reforms in the west African country.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, the IMF is currently negotiating on behalf of
Nigeria a debt relief from the Paris Club to which Nigeria owes more than
70 percent of 28 billion U.S. Dollars external debt.
</P>
<P>
But, the Paris Club is insisting that for it to grant the relief,
Nigeria must put in place some economic reforms which the IMF is willing to
support.
</P>
<P>
Some of the reform requirements include abolition of dual exchange rate,
removal subsidies and continuation of the privatization program, said the
paper, adding that most of them had already been implemented by the
Nigerian government.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria is one of the highly indebted poor countries in the world which
are qualified for debt relief from the Paris Club if it successfully
implements its reform program.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria is supposed to pay about 4 billion Dollars debt service
annually, but currently is able to pay 1.5 billion Dollars.
</P>
<P>
If Nigeria maintains a track record of performance, it could be
entitled to about 60 percent cut from its stock of external debts,
according to the paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
