<HEADLINE> Toxic Pollution Attains Dangerous Level in Islamabad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Islamabad, the capital city of
Pakistan, is facing serious pollution problems as formaldehyde gas
in the environment has reached a dangerous level.
</P>
<P>
This was the result of an initial report based on a first ever
study of toxic pollution in the city being conducted by the
Capital Development Authority (CDA) and the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP).
</P>
<P>
According to sources from CDA, the central engineering
laboratory of CDA with the coordination of Haider Khawaja, a UNDP
consultant from Albany university, New York, took samples of air,
soil and water to examine level of formaldehyde, nitric acid and
other hydro carbons in Islamabad's sector I-8/1 and the suburban
village of Saidpur.
</P>
<P>
The comparative study of both areas will help determine the
level of pollution, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Sajjad Ali Shah, assistant director of the central engineering
laboratory, said Wednesday that citizens of Islamabad are inhaling
in large quantity of suspended particles of less than ten microns
which contain poisonous materials.
</P>
<P>
He said the samples will be sent to New York for study and the
final report will be released within a few months.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the broad spectrum study of toxic pollution
is the first ever conducted in Pakistan and the result will help
concerned authorities take measures to control pollution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
