<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rebound in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rebounded in Tokyo
Wednesday following declines in the previous three trading days,
helped by an increase in index futures prices and stable moves in
the foreign exchange and bond markets.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange surged 235.72 points, or 1.78
percent, from Tuesday's close to end at 13,468.46.
</P>
<P>
The broader based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering
all First Section issues, rose 10.43 points or 0.99 percent to
1,058.76.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section decreased to an estimated 282.43
million shares from Tuesday's 340.87 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Sumitomo Metal Industries was the day's most heavily traded
issue.
</P>
<P>
Despite Wednesday's rise, traders said Tokyo stocks still lack
enough upward momentum to surge further as investors have
lingering concern about the yen's advance against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. dollar was quoted at 112.57-60 yen at 3 p.m. local
time, 6 a.m. GMT, up from 111.51-54 yen late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Traders said that investors will remain hesitant to buy stocks
before they ascertain the future trends in the foreign exchange
and bond markets.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, gainers outnumbered
losers 804 to 313, with 173 issues ending the day unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
