<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish PM Designate to Return Mandate for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister designate
Yalim Erez announced here Tuesday that he will return his mandate
for a government formation to President Suleyman Demirel.
</P>
<P>
Erez, an independent lawmaker and industry and trade
minister, made the announcement two days after True Path Party
(DYP) leader Tansu Ciller declared her sudden support for a
proposal for a minority government led by Democratic Left Party
(DSP) leader and former prime minister designate Bulent Ecevit.
</P>
<P>
Erez said that he will soon meet with outgoing Prime Minister
and Motherland Party (ANAP) leader Mesut Yilmaz, Ecevit and other
party leaders.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey is the most important for me" and the country can not
remain without government, added Erez.
</P>
<P>
Following Ciller's decision to support a DSP minority
government, Yilmaz and Ecevit called on Erez to return his
mandate for the government formation to Demirel.
</P>
<P>
Erez, a businessman-turned-politician, was chosen partly
because he sided with the pro-secular establishment.
</P>
<P>
He resigned as industry and trade minister in a earlier
coalition between Ciller's DYP and pro-Islamic Welfare Party (RP)
in 1997, two months after the military warned the government to
strictly act on the secular constitution.
</P>
<P>
On December 23, Demirel appointed Erez to form a new
government as Ecevit failed to get enough support in parliament.
</P>
<P>
Demirel said he believed an independent lawmaker could obtain
wide support from Turkey's bickering political parties.
</P>
<P>
The government led by Yilmaz, who is now acting prime
minister, collapsed in November in a no-confidence vote as a
result of his corruption scandals.
</P>
<P>
Demirel did not appoint the leader of the largest party to
form a cabinet as such an appointment will bring the pro-Islamic
Virtue Party (FP) to power, thus infuriating pro-secular
military. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
