<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Delay on Palestinian Statehood: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinians will declare
an independent state on May 4 as Israel's settlement expansion and
suspension of a recent peace deal left them with no alternatives,
a senior Palestinian official has said.
</P>
<P>
"There has been no change in the policy of the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) on this matter," PNA Planning Minister
Nabil Sha'ath was quoted Wednesday by The Jerusalem Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
What has made the declaration of statehood more necessary,
Shaath told the newspaper in an exclusive interview, "is the
total lack of implementation of the Wye agreement and the total
lack of progress on permanent status (talks)."
</P>
<P>
In response to his remarks, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's
spokesman Aviv Bushinsky accused Shaath of "announcing
unilaterally" on the establishment of a Palestinian state, saying
the Palestinians are to blame for the stalemate in the Wye
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The recrimination has characterized the Israeli-Palestinian
relationship over the last several weeks since Netanyahu halted
the implementation of the Wye agreement citing alleged Palestinian
violations.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians said they have fulfilled all their
obligations and blasted Netanyahu for procrastinating in order to
woo right-wingers and extremists.
</P>
<P>
As the election campaign is under way in Israel, the
Palestinian statehood has become a focus in the peace process as
well as in Israel's domestic politics.
</P>
<P>
PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat has repeated his pledge that he
will declare a Palestinian state on May 4, when the five-year
interim period set in the Oslo accords ends, with or without an
agreement with Israel.
</P>
<P>
But since Israel sets the election date on May 17, two weeks
after the Oslo deadline, the Palestinians have been debating over
whether to go ahead with their plan to declare statehood and have
sent mixed signals on this issue.
</P>
<P>
Some officials said the PNA will be flexible on its agenda for
the statehood, fearing a unilateral declaration would help bring a
hard-line Israeli government to power.
</P>
<P>
Other officials, however, said the statehood issue has nothing
to do with the elections in Israel, vowing to go ahead as
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Egypt and the European Union have tried in
recent weeks to convince the PNA that it is in the interest of
the Palestinians to postpone such a unilateral declaration until
after the Israeli elections.
</P>
<P>
Arafat will meet with U.S. President Bill Clinton later in the
spring to discuss the troubled peace process and the Palestinian
statehood is expected to be one of the major topics in the talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
