<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Infant Mortality Down, Death by Cancer Up in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Latest statistics showed a
sharp decline in infant mortality and death by heart diseases but
a slight growth in death resulting from cancerous tumors in Israel
in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
Infant mortality rate has fallen by half in the decade but the
gap between Jewish and non-Jewish Israelis remains, according to a
recent book published by Israel's Health Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The overall infant mortality rate was 6.3 for every 1,000
births in 1997, with 5.0 among Jews and 9.3 deaths for every 1,000
births among non-Jews, almost twice as high, the figures show.
</P>
<P>
Between 1984 and 1995, the rate of death by ischemic heart
diseases -- when the heart muscle does not get enough oxygen to
work properly -- fell 23 percent among Jewish men and 18 percent
among Jewish women, according to the book.
</P>
<P>
Over the same period, death by vascular diseases in the brain
fell 35 percent among Jewish women and by 17 percent among Jewish
men.
</P>
<P>
The book, which was quoted by the Haaretz daily Wednesday, said
that the Israelis are also spending less time in hospital.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Israelis spent 785 days in hospital for every 1,000
people, compared with 1,037 days in 1975. The average length of
hospital stay fell from eight days in 1975 to 4.3 days in 1997.
</P>
<P>
But the figures also show that the rate of death by
cancerous tumors among Jews rose by 7 percent for males and 4
percent for females from 1984 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
The daily calorie intake of the average Israeli increased 14
percent between 1990 and 1997, from an average of 3,089 calories a
day in 1990 to 3,570 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
A study covering the period between April and September 1996
found that 7.8 percent of the population suffer from high blood
pressure, 3.7 percent have asthma, 3.3 percent have diabetes, and
2.6 percent of Israelis have heart blockages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing's Projects Marking 50th Anniversary Progress Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The 67 major Beijing projects
scheduled for completion to mark the 50th anniversary of the
founding of New China in October this year will be completed
within the year, according to Vice-Mayor Wang Guangtao.
</P>
<P>
The wide-ranging projects involving infrastructure, science and
education, trade and cultural facilities and residential housing,
will be completed at a total cost of 110 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Wang said 10 projects, including a large bookstore, a financial
center, an expressway to the Great Wall, a water plant, and a
medical science research center, have been completed, and the
remaining projects are progressing smoothly.
</P>
<P>
"The selected projects represent the image of the Chinese
capital and fully demonstrate China's planning and construction
level," said Wang.
</P>
<P>
Executive Vice-Mayor Liu Qi said Beijing plans to invest 124.5
billion yuan in fixed assets during 1999, up 10 percent from last
year.
</P>
<P>
The People's Republic of China, or New China, was founded on
October 1, 1949.  
</P>
</TEXT>
