<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Apple Unveils New Version of PCs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Apple Computer Inc. Tuesday
launched a new desktop computer for businesses, in a bid to
continue the momentum it has found in the mass market with its
wildly popular Mac, the company said.
</P>
<P>
The Power Mac G3 is the most powerful iMac ever built and the
most powerful PC in the industry, said Steve Jobs, interim chief
executive at the resurgent computer company.
</P>
<P>
The new desktop G3 is professional computer which aimed at
graphic designers and home users with a thirst for graphics-heavy
power, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
Apple also is trying to increase its appeal to computer game
players. Analysts noted the company boosted the ability of its G3
computer to play games with three-dimensional graphics and
unveiled a new device that enables Mac users to play about 100
different software games designed for Sony's PlayStation video
game system.
</P>
<P>
The new version of the G3 comes as Apple also reports strong
sales of its iMac, which is aimed at easing users onto the
Internet. Since the iMac hit the shelves in mid-August, more than
800,000 units have been shipped, Jobs said during a keynote
address at the MacWorld Expo in San Franciso.
</P>
<P>
Building on the marketing momentum generated by the
translucent,turquoise-hued iMacs, Apple said it would offer the
new iMacs with a faster processor and colors ranging from lime to
blueberry at a price of 1,199 U.S. dollars, 100 dollars down from
a prior suggested price of 1,299 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The iMacs is now available in red, orange, purple, and green
as well as its original color, teal.
</P>
<P>
Most personal computers are sold in beige or sometimes black,
but the recent popularity of the iMac is leading other
manufacturers to break with convention.
</P>
<P>
Apple's sales peaked in its fiscal 1995. Since then, revenue
has tailed off during the past years. However, the company did
earn money in its most recent years after losing one billion
dollars in the fiscal 1997 year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
