<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Backpedals Nearly Half a U.S. Cent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar
backpedaled nearly half a U.S. cent Wednesday, whittled away by a
stronger U.S. dollar and a near 12-year low in copper prices.
</P>
<P>
Westpac Banking Corporation chief foreign exchange dealer Peter
McGrath said the domestic currency pulled back from recent gains,
impacted by U.S. dollar strength against several currencies.
</P>
<P>
McGrath said despite gains in the Commodity Research Bureau
Index, weakness in base metals - particularly copper - had eaten
away at the commodity-sensitive Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
At the close of trade the local unit was buying 61.98 U.S.
cents compared with 62.43 late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During the day it traded between 61.95 and 62.30 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
"There was just a little bit of a pull-back here today from
recent gains," McGrath said.
</P>
<P>
The euro, yen, Australian and New Zealand dollars were weaker
against the U.S. dollar, he said.
</P>
<P>
The new European currency also fell against the Australian
dollar, finishing at 1.8899 Australian dollars from 1.8924
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
McGrath said there had been a long "run-down" in the U.S.
dollar recently and the strength was probably simply the result of
profit taking.
</P>
<P>
"Also, some of the rises in commodities in the last few days
have hidden some weakness in some of the base metals, which is not
good for Aussie," McGrath said.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark three-month London Metal Exchange price Wednesday
hit its lowest level since May 1987, with three-month copper
quoted at 1,438/42 U.S. dollars a ton at midday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Australian Bureau of Statistics retail sales data
out Wednesday had little impact on the market.
</P>
<P>
November retail sales were softer than expected, up a
seasonally adjusted 0.3 percent from an upwardly revised rise of
1.0 percent in October.
</P>
<P>
At the local close, the Australian dollar was trading at 69.74
Japanese yen from 69.57. 
</P>
</TEXT>
