<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Monitor Fishing Activities by Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Deputy Minister of Agriculture
and Fisheries Isidora Faztudo has said the country will enhance its
monitoring on fishing activities in coastal areas through satellite
starting from this March.
</P>
<P>
The new system is aimed at cracking down on abuse of fishing by illegal
ships. It is estimated that the new system will cost 4.6 million U.S.
Dollars, the Noticias reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The program, said Faztudo on Tuesday, includes monitoring on fishing
boats and fishing activities. It will help detect ships fishing in the
Mozambican territorial waters to see if they have the licenses for fishing
in an approved area.
</P>
<P>
"In the circumstances, we need to obtain information on the catchments,
and specific resources within certain period of time, which means we need
to strengthen management on fishing activities," said the deputy minister.
</P>
<P>
The new monitoring system will involve the Mozambican navy.
</P>
<P>
"The monitoring on Mozambican coasts should engage the Mozambican armed
forces, since some ships illegally fishing on the Mozambican coast are
equipped with weapons," said Defense Minister Aguiar Mazula.
</P>
<P>
The government plans to deploy new patrol boats and establish a
monitoring center in the capital Maputo.
</P>
<P>
 A preliminary 15 boats will be equipped with electrical facilities to
detect and receive satellite signals, with all industrial and semi-
industrial fishing boats getting equipped later.
</P>
<P>
 Meanwhile, relevant laws and regulations are already on the way, while
technical personnel have been trained ready for deployment at the end of
this month.
</P>
<P>
"The satellite monitoring system will benefit not only fishermen but
also be conducive to the assessment and reasonable exploitation of fishing
resources," said Faztudo.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique boasts a coast line of over 2,600 kilometers. However, due
to lack of capital and poor technical strength, there is little efficient
protection on its fishing resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
