<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Defense Ministry to Be Restructured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 6 (Xinhua) -- In a significant move, India's
Defense Ministry announced Tuesday that it had initiated a process
to restructure itself which included integration of the three
services headquarters with the ministry.
</P>
<P>
As a first step, according to the Times of India Wednesday, the
ministry would begin a series of presentations and interactions
between the ministry and the three services headquarters to
formulate concrete proposals.
</P>
<P>
The first meeting will be held on Friday and the blueprint is
expected to be ready by the end of this month, the daily said.
</P>
<P>
The decision on restructuring was taken at the defense
minister's weekly meeting on Tuesday following the dismissal of
Admiral Vishnu Bhagwat from the post of Navy chief and the removal
of Ajit Kumar from the post of defense secretary in controversial
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
The dismissal and removal of the generals raised vital
questions regarding coordination between the service chiefs and
the bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
Integrating the services headquarters with the Defense Ministry
has reportedly been a long-pending demand of the armed forces and,
over three months ago, Defense Minister George Fernandes asked the
three service chiefs to submit proposals for the restructuring.
</P>
<P>
Indian armed forces do not have a role in the decision-making
process, let alone any significant authority relating to
purchases.
</P>
<P>
Although the three service chiefs enjoy the same status as
cabinet secretary, they can only submit proposals when it comes to
deciding on military equipment.
</P>
<P>
The decision-making power rests with defense ministry
bureaucrats who are often accused by the services of lacking both
commitment and in-depth understanding of defense issues, thus
relations between the armed forces and the ministry's bureaucracy
have historically been strained.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
