<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Banks Prepare for Millennium Bug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines banks have
started preparing its computer systems against any possible
introduction of the so-called "millennium bug" that threatens the
information technology at the turn of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
In a report released here Wednesday, the Philippine
Presidential Commission on Year 2000 said that with the millennium
bug expected to strike less than a year from now, at least two
major banks are laying the groundwork for Y2K preparations.
</P>
<P>
One major bank is now in the midst of Y2K conversion of its
mainframe systems, and expects to complete the process by the
middle of this year, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
It said that another bank purchased new mainframes for its
computer system in 1997, and converted all transaction systems to
be Y2K compliant.
</P>
<P>
However, the commission did not name the two major banks which
are preparing for the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
The commission said that banks are one of the seven areas it
has warned to be prepared for the millennium bug due to their
crucial services in daily life.
</P>
<P>
Also deemed as crucial sectors are utilities,
tele-communications, transport, health care, manufacturing and
government services in the country, it said.
</P>
<P>
The millennium bug is a built-in flaw in older computer systems
that use two digits to determine the date. Such computers may fail
on January 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Effects of the millennium bug include erroneous cancellation of
customer orders or shipments of goods and supplies, premature
expiration of licenses and credit cards, and miscalculation or
non-payment of salaries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
