<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Indonesia Struggling to Achieve Budget's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Finance Minister
Bambang Subianto believed the 1999/2000 draft state budget
reflects the government's wish to let the economy recover soon,
and analysts said the realization of the budget will depend
largely on the political stability in the country.
</P>
<P>
Set for the 1999/2000 fiscal year beginning in April and ending
in March next year, the tightened and balanced draft budget,
unveiled by President B.J. Habibie on Tuesday, assumes zero
economic growth, 17 percent inflation and a rupiah-U.S. dollar
exchange rate of 7,500 rupiah.
</P>
<P>
The government's wish to bring about economic recovery could be
seen from the assumptions it had made about revenues and economic
growth, Bambang said.
</P>
<P>
Domestic revenues from non-oil commodities were projected at
119.8 trillion rupiah or higher than last year's figure of 99.5
trillion rupiah, while oil and gas revenue would make up just 14.9
percent of total domestic revenue compared with 33.3 percent in
1998/1999.
</P>
<P>
Such an assumption was realistic, and the government was
optimistic that the target would be achieved, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
However, some economists questioned if it will be possible to
see zero growth given the unfavorable economic condition and
political uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
"The result of the general election scheduled to be held in
June and the new administration will play a big role in economic
growth. Political stability will be the key to economic recovery
and growth," said Pande Radja Silalahi, a researcher from the
Center for Strategic and International Studies.
</P>
<P>
Banking analyst Nyoman Moena said that the government target to
keep inflation rate at 17 percent and the rupiah at 7,500 against
the U.S. dollar is too optimistic considering that the government
will allocate more funds for food subsidies, foreign debt
repayments, and the social safety net program.
</P>
<P>
"The number of poor people this year is five times higher than
the figure before the economic crisis, thus the government should
provide more money for this," he said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts noted that the zero-growth budget relies heavily on
foreign loans because prices of traditional revenue-earner oil are
projected to remain at record lows.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign revenues both in terms of program loans and project
loans will still be needed because domestic revenues cannot be
expected to fulfill the budget needs yet," President Habibie noted
when delivering the budget before the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The 1999/2000 budget expects foreign loans of 77.4 trillion
rupiah in 1999/2000 as against 114.6 trillion rupiah in 1998/1999,
with program loans contributing 47.40 trillion rupiah and project
loans making up 30 trillion rupiah.
</P>
<P>
This is a big question mark, said Silalahi. "Could we get that
much (77.4 trillion rupiah)?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
The largest chunk of routine expenditures is allocated for
interest payments, costing about 44.43 trillion rupiah, on
government debts.
</P>
<P>
It is 31 percent lower than the amount allocated in the current
budget, due to the strengthening of the rupiah and last year's
agreement with the Paris Club creditor nations to suspend
principal payment on the country's bilateral borrowings for two
years starting 1998/1999.
</P>
<P>
Another huge burden for the budget is the 18 trillion rupiah
allocated for recapitalization of the banking sector.
</P>
<P>
"The proposed fund for the bank restructuring is much higher
than those allocated to other sectors, making it politically
impossible to be accommodated by the House of Representatives,"
said Rijanto Sastroatmodjo, a leading banking observer.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the government need 34 trillion rupiah to
recapitalize troubled banks. The remaining 16 trillion rupiah will
be acquired by the government from the sales of assets of
take-over banks and suspended ones.
</P>
<P>
Analyst Didiek J. Rachbini said that the government is too
optimistic about the sale of assets of insolvent banks given the
unfavorable economic condition.
</P>
<P>
Economic observer Umar Juoro advised the government to carry
out strict measures to select the banks which would be given the
recapitalization assistance.
</P>
<P>
Outlining his first draft budget to the House, Habibie stressed
that the recovery of the country's economy from the 18-month-old
crisis would depend heavily on the success of restoring the
banking sector and the real sector.
</P>
<P>
Consistent with its recent moves to promote small businesses,
the government also plans to allocate a significant portion of the
development budget to foster small and medium-sized enterprises
and cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
The government also aims to make agriculture the backbone of
the country's economy, earmarking 4.4 trillion rupiah to the
sector.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the draft budget, the Jakarta Post said there is
a larger and more telling "if" upon which the accuracy of the
government's financial planning hinges.
</P>
<P>
"The budget assumes that the markets and the public will have
strong confidence in the government, which in turn hinges on
political and social stability, neither of which can be
guaranteed," the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Firmer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Strong leads from Asian and
northern hemisphere markets inspired a rally on the local share
market Wednesday, reversing Tuesday's losses.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index ended 37.8 points firmer at
2,853.4 which countered Tuesday's 17.0 point loss and returned the
market to the upward trend begun on December 15.
</P>
<P>
No individual sector stood out in the rally with key stocks in
each sector outperforming their rivals, although the all
industrials, up 74.1 to 5,158.6 points, again outperformed the all
resources, 6.5 points higher at 959.8.
</P>
<P>
National turnover stood at 367.05 million shares worth 1.13
billion Australian dollars (700.6 million U.S. dollars) with 700
stocks higher, 561 lower and 411 steady.
</P>
<P>
Brokers attributed the day's rise to the strong leads from Hong
Kong, Japan and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's Hang Seng index had jumped 198.2 points to 10,089.2
shortly before its close, Japan's Nikkei rose 235.0 to 13,468.0
after the U.S. Dow Jones Industrial Average closed up 126.92 at
9,311.19 points overnight.
</P>
<P>
The stand-out stocks included Foster's - 19 cents firmer,
Woolworths - 25 higher, Coca-Cola Amatil - 18 stronger, and
Brambles continued its strong run of recent days with a 1.60
Australian dollars rise.
</P>
<P>
Insurance major AMP was the only major to lose ground over the
day, drifting 21 cents.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector was led higher by major Westpac and junior
Macquarie Bank. The banking index closed 117.8 points higher to
6,591.3.
</P>
<P>
Westpac jumped 40 cents, the other majors were quieter with
National Australia up 28.4, ANZ was 23.2 higher and Commonwealth
was 18.5 stronger.
</P>
<P>
The telecommunications sector dropped some intraday gains to
close 18.4 points higher overall at 1,851.9 points after peaking
at 1,883.8 in the day.
</P>
<P>
C&AMP;W Optus gained three cents to close, and Telstra gained
eight.
</P>
<P>
BHP was the star performer in the resources sector as it
reversed recent weakness to close 35 cents (three percent) higher.
</P>
<P>
Gold bullion closed trading in Sydney at 286.95 U.S. dollars an
ounce compared with Tuesday's close of 287.05. 
</P>
</TEXT>
