<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's N. Bank Announces Freeze on Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NAIROBI, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The cash-strapped National Bank of
Kenya (NBK) has announced an immediate freeze on further lending in efforts
to conserve liquidity and save the fourth-largest bank in the country from
collapse.
</P>
<P>
Also frozen are staff recruitment and expansion of branch network,
the new NBK Managing Director, Reuben Marambi, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
 Although lending was the main business of banks, it was vital that the
exercise was halted while the new management was trying to put in place
appropriate internal controls to ensure proper practices, he was quoted by
Wednesday's press reports as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, Marambi emphasized that the new move was temporary and would
 be suspended as soon as the new team settles down.
</P>
<P>
 Meanwhile, he said the NBK will take "appropriate steps" to recover
billions of Shillings owed by some high-profile Kenyans including two
cabinet ministers and the deputy speaker.
</P>
<P>
 The bank collected over 2.7 billion Shillings (about 45 million U.S.
Dollars) of the bad and doubtful debts last year.
</P>
<P>
Marambi also confirmed that the government is determined to sell off
its remaining 22.5 percent stake in the bank thereby reducing its influence.
</P>
<P>
The bank, with 23 billion Shillings in assets, has 29 branches across
 this east African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
