<HEADLINE> Saddam Incites to Topple Pro-U.S. Arab Governments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
on Wednesday called for overthrowing the Arab governments that
support the United States and Britain against Iraq, the Iraqi News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In a nationally televised speech on the occasion of the
National Army Day, Saddam slammed those Arab governments that
"cooperate with U.S. and British forces in the Gulf region."
</P>
<P>
Saddam agitated Arab masses to "rise up" against what he called
"errant Arab rulers."
</P>
<P>
"It is time for you to revolt, sons of the Arab world, sons of
the Arab Gulf, to revolt against foreigners, to revolt against
their forces. It is time to kick them out of your countries," said
Saddam.
</P>
<P>
He said that one who antagonizes any Arab country is the enemy
of all Arabs.
</P>
<P>
Saddam condemned the presence of U.S. and British aircraft in
the no-fly zones over northern and southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain imposed two no-fly zones in Iraq after the
1991 Gulf War to protect the minority Kurds in the north and
Shiite Muslims in the south from "Baghdad's oppression."
</P>
<P>
Iraq calls the no-fly zones illegal and vows to fire at any
planes that violate its airspace. Since late last month, Iraqi
air-defense force and U.S.-British planes have traded fires four
times in the no-fly zones.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Iraqi jets confronted U.S. warplanes in the
southern no-fly zone, the first time since the imposition of the
no-fly zones about eight years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
