<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Automakers Report Strong Sales In 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Most American, European and
Japanese automakers Tuesday reported higher sales of cars and
light trucks for 1998, according to reports from Detroit.
</P>
<P>
Ford Motor Co., the second largest automaker in the United
States, said its sales increased 7 percent in December over
year-ago levels. For the year of 1998, Ford's sales rose 2
percent for its best year since 1978.
</P>
<P>
DaimlerChrysler also had its best year ever, with a 9 percent
increase over 1997. For December, sales were up 7 percent. The
figures do not include DaimlerChrysler's results for
Mercedes-Benz, which are reported separately.
</P>
<P>
Major European automakers, including Mercedes-Benz, BMW and
Volkswagen, said their sales zoomed in the year.
</P>
<P>
Mercedes-Benz set a record for the year, with sales up 39
percent. Volkswagen's sales for the year were up 59 percent, its
best year since 1981.
</P>
<P>
Other automakers including General Motors Corp., the world's
largest automaker in the world, planned to release their figures
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Of the Japanese automakers reporting Tuesday, Isuzu Motor
Corp.said its December sales jumped 31.6 percent and the sales
for 1998 were up 11.3 percent. Mazda Motor Corp. also had a 13.5
percent increase for December and an 8.4 percent increase for the
passing year.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi Motor Corp. had a 16.7 percent rise of sales in
December, but had a slight decline of sales for the whole year.
In Nissan Motor Co Ltd, which had an 11.9 percent gain for
December, sales for the year dropped 14.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Among S.Korean automakers, sales for Kia Motors Corp. products
rose 49.8 percent for 1998 while sales for Hyundai Motor Co.
vehicles were down 20 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts and executives said a strong economy was behind the
surge of sales of vehicles in the United States and Europe, while
most of Japanese and S. Korean automakers are still struggling
for the improvement of future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
