<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Continues Pro-active Fiscal Policies in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 6 (Xinhua) -- China will continue to pursue
pro-active fiscal policies and expand financial expenditure in
1999 in a move to boost economic growth, Xiang Huaicheng,
Minister of Finance, announced at a press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
As one of the major steps, China plans to issue a total of
316.5 billion yuan in treasury bonds this year, with the
government budgetary deficit designed at 105.3 billion yuan, more
than the figure of 96 billion yuan in 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
Presently, the central government has no plan to issue
special treasury bonds in 1999 to recapitalize commercial banks,
but he did not rule out the possibility of issuing such bonds
when necessary.
</P>
<P>
He said that, considering the present low price levels and
economic operation conditions, the increased deficit will not
lead to inflation.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the central government hopes to issue
a certain amount of state sovereignty bonds on the international
market this year, as it did last year, not because China is short
of 500 million or one billion US dollars but because it is keen
to become more involved in the global capital market.
</P>
<P>
He said that in 1998 China's pro-active fiscal policies
yielded good results in boosting economic growth and readjusting
the investment structure, but warned that exports are still on
the downslide accompanied by sluggish enterprise investments and
domestic consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
He warned that if the financial expenditure was to be cut
this year, it would be difficult to maintain a steady growth of
the national economy.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the devastating floods in many parts of
China last summer have created a huge demand for rebuilding and
rehabilitation, and the reform of state-owned enterprises is now
at a crucial stage, both calling for stronger financial support
this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China will establish a basic financial framework
for public services in line with China's socialist market
economy, Xiang said, adding that the government has spent too
much in sectors that should not have been of its concern,
especially in the competitive production sectors, and too little
on social and public needs, which fall within the scope of
government obligations.
</P>
<P>
"Eliminating expenditure from the former sectors and inve
sting more in the latter is what setting up a financial framework
for public services should be about," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
In the long run, however, China will maintain a moderately
tight fiscal stance, with a view to achieving a balanced budget,
and establishing a policy framework and institutional set-up to
promote enterprise investment and private consumption, the
minister added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
