<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Currency Now Available to More Chinese Families </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Almost every family in the
cities of Beijing and Shanghai has some foreign currency of some
kind, a recent survey of the residents of these two cities found.
</P>
<P>
The survey was intended to find out how families in the two
cities got their foreign currency and what their attitude is
towards it.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen percent of those said they got it from their work,
and 11 percent said they got it from moonlighting. Some said it
was given by relatives, friends, or other sources.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-six percent of those surveyed will put their foreign
currency in banks, to let it increase in value, because foreign
currencies have relatively higher interest rates than the
national currency renminbi, whose interest rate has been cut six
times since May, 1996. But, 22 percent of those surveyed still
prefer to stash their currency at home. When asked about
converting some of it into renminbi, 66 percent said they would
not, while 11 percent thought it was a good idea.
</P>
<P>
According to the State Administration of Foreign Exchange,
China's citizens have 80 billion US. dollars worth of foreign
currency, in addition to the state's 140 billion dollars in
reserves.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Computer-related Crimes Surging in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An increasing portion of hackers, however, are not merely
young computer whizzes, but rather electronic bandits who get
away with a tremendous amount of stolen assets. The Hao brothers
in east China's Jiangsu Province transmitted 260,000 yuan to
their own account from a local bank via a computer network, and
the two were sentenced to capital punishment last month.
</P>
<P>
Some other hackers maliciously broke into other computer
systems, paralyzing the entire network. Yang Wei, a post-graduate
at China's prestigious Fudan University, was prosecuted recently
for illegally using a company's network for over 2,000 hours and
causing 160 million yuan in economic loss.
</P>
<P>
To safeguard national security and penalize hackers, China's
latest Criminal Law has added new provisions to "combat
computer-related crimes." The government has also promulgated a
series of regulations to set criteria for information-system
security and oversee the testing and sales of computer security
products.
</P>
<P>
Apart from legal backup, the role of technical measures cannot
be overemphasized. "Given that all the hardware and computer
chips we use are made by foreign companies; the operating systems
are developed by foreign companies, and even the security
hierarchy of computer products are set by foreign standards, I
think 'security' based on alien technologies is unsafe and
unreliable." CASS's Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
He urges that China put more human and economic resources into
developing a comprehensive and copyrighted computer coding system
so that China will not have to completely rely on imported coding
products.
</P>
<P>
Chinese companies are aware of the hacker problem, and China's
Network Security Ally organized by China's information security
departments will be established this May, with major network
users and corporate and individual computer security-product
producers as its main component.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, scores of computer network security companies are
emerging all over China, fostering a new growth outlet for
China's computer industry.
</P>
<P>
China's public security departments, now the only watchdog for
computer-related crimes, are busy introducing a nationwide
hacker-monitoring system to find these new-age criminals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
