<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Euro Gains Against Kenyan Shilling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NAIROBI, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The newly launched Euro currency made a
strong debut on the Kenyan money market to exchange with the Shilling at a
mean rate of 72.9325 Shillings, according to statistics released by the
Central Bank of Kenya (CBK).
</P>
<P>
 The Euro was bought at 72.6351 Shillings and sold at 73.2298 Shillings
at Tuesday's trading, the East African Standard newspaper reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, the CBK advised Kenyan investors not to replace all their
foreign exchange reserves with Euro, at least in the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
 Local banks have equally been told to closely monitor movements of the
Euro in relation to other international currencies, noted the CBK weekly
update.
</P>
<P>
 Most of the local commercial banks traded the Euro beginning this week.
</P>
<P>
The Euro offered Tuesday at an average exchange rate of 72.94 Shillings
for buying, while average selling stood at 73.70 Shillings.
</P>
<P>
 The Kenyan Shilling edged lower against the Dollar in active trade on
Tuesday, and commercial bank dealers said the market had nearly adjusted to
the introduction of a single European currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
 Dealers also said they saw some Dollar demand from the corporates
sector and that Dollar inflows mainly from the tea sector have failed to
match that demand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
