<HEADLINE> Zambia's Coke Firm's Excise Duty to Be Reduced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LUSAKA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Coca Cola firm in Zambia is still
optimistic that the Zambian government will keep its promise to reduce the
high excise duty on Coca Cola, Zambia Daily Mail reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted company managing director Ian Ackerman as saying
that one day the governent will look at the issue of the duty, and bring it
to more economical le "We have continued hold meetings with government
and other relevant authorities over the matter, and we are hopeful that one
day the discussions would bear fruit," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that his firm will not move out of the country despite losing
business, which has now slumped to about 75 percent to imported Coca Cola
from the country's neighboring countries and local produced juices.
</P>
<P>
Coca Cola has pledged some 75 million U.S. dollars investment over a
five-year program should the government abides by the agreement to reduce
the excise duty.
</P>
<P>
Last September the firm increased the prices of its products, Coca Cola,
 fanta and sprite by 80 percent from 500 kwacha to 900 kwacha a bottle
because of what it called high duty imposed on raw materials.
</P>
<P>
Last May the government promised to reduce the excise duty on the
drinks from 25 percent to five percent, but failed to meet its promise.
</P>
</TEXT>
