<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nyerere: Privatization Leads to Commercial Colonization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 DAR ES SALAAM, January 6 (Xinhua) --The on-going privatization move in
Tanzania will put the economy in the hands of foreigners and lead to the
commercial colonization of the country, Tanzanian founding president Julius
Nyerere has warned.
</P>
<P>
He told a religious seminar in the northern town of Arusha Monday that
developed countries' pushing for opening the market and privatizing the
economy is for their own gains, media reports here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The push for privatization in Tanzania is the push for the
foreignization of the economy, " Nyerere said.
</P>
<P>
The well-known African statesman also warned that developed countries
are preparing a law called the "Multi-national Investment Agreement" (MIA)
which would give their investors more freedom to invest in third world
countries at the expense of indigenous businessmen.
</P>
<P>
"When MIA becomes a binding law, it will be mandatory for authorities
in Tanzania to treat an investor from Michigan the same way as they treat a
Chagga tribe investor from Hai (in the north)," he said. "There is not a
single Tanzanian investor who can go to the United States and start a
business there."
</P>
<P>
Nyerere singled out the pending privatization of the National Bank of
Commerce (1997) Limited as being a result of pressure from the rich and
powerful developed countries.
</P>
<P>
"They come to Tanzania and tell us: 'Open up your market.' Then they
say: 'NBC is too big, we can't compete it...privatize it, break it up.'
Really, this is the arrogance of power," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Ironically, in their countries, when banks are in trouble, they don't
privatize them. Instead, they are helped by the State or merge with another
profit-making banking institution," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere also said that the privatization of Tanzanian economy would
continue to increase the growing gap between the rich and the poor.
</P>
<P>
"It is very easy to produce millionaires... What is difficult is the
abolition of poverty," he said. "It has always been true everywhere in the
liberalization and privatization of the economy, the small minority make
money, become rich and powerful while the vast majority become poorer and
poorer."
</P>
<P>
Nyerere made the remarks on Monday evening when addressing the fourth
Provincial Chapter of the East African Province of the Holy Ghost held at
the Spiritan Missionary Seminary at Njiro on the outskirts of Arusha.
</P>
<P>
The chapter was attended by more than 30 delegates from Tanzania, Kenya,
 Uganda, Zambia, the Democratic Republic of Congo, Senegal, Guinea-Bissau,
Congo-Brazzaville, and countries from Europe and North America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
