<HEADLINE> China Active in Cultural Exchanges in 1998 (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 6 (Xinhua) -- When Chinese folk music was
introduced to the rest of the world at Vienna's Golden Hall in
early 1998 as a new year's treat, it was the beginning of a
series of cultural exchanges between China and the other parts of
the world.
</P>
<P>
In September, Beijing's Forbidden City was given greater
attention when the well-known Chinese director Zhang Yimou
cooperated with the Maggio Musicale Fiorentino in a spectacular
version of Puccini's opera Turandot on its original site.
</P>
<P>
Culture Minister Sun Jiazheng has said that China's overall
cultural contacts with the outside world made greater progress in
1998. According to the ministry, China had 1,300 exchange
activities with about 20,000 people involved in 1998. China also
signed cultural agreements with Central Africa and Yemen, new
executive plans with over 20 countries, and a memorandum of
understanding with Canada.
</P>
<P>
Last February, over 500 relics from museums in 17 provinces
were put on display in the US., with United Nations Secre
tary-General Kofi Annan attending the opening ceremony of China's
largest display abroad.
</P>
<P>
Some famous musical groups also came to China, including the
Cleveland Orchestra, the New York Philharmonic, the Kirov
Orchestra of Mariinsky Theater, and the Opera National de
Paris.
</P>
</TEXT>
