<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Appeals for Urgent Food Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Prime Minister Frederick
Sumaye has appealed to the international community to provide urgent food
assistance to his country as 13 out of 20 Mainland regions are facing an
acute shortage of food.
</P>
<P>
From now to July, Tanzania will have a food deficit of some 600,000
tons, Sumaye was quoted by Wednesday's media reports as saying.
</P>
<P>
Addressing foreign envoys here Tuesday, he said a recent
government survey ending last week found that 13 regions on the mainland
are seriously affected by food shortage, with eight of them being
vulnerable to famine.
</P>
<P>
In the northeastern, central and coastal parts of the country, most of
the planted crops had dried up due to lack of precipitation in the short
rains season starting last October. The food situation is worsened by
attacks of pests, rodents and quelea quelea birds.
</P>
<P>
"In some regions, people are reported to have depleted their food
stocks and they are now facing serious shortages...this would lead to
famine for the poorest and most vulnerable of our people," the Prime
Minister was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"It is our hope that donors will come to assist us in solving this
serious food crisis," he said. Meanwhile, he added the government "is doing
all within its disposal to avert possible loss of lives among the general
public."
</P>
<P>
Sumaye said the government has released 35,000 tons of food from the
Strategic Grain Reserves to the market and will import 50,000 tons of food
on emergency basis.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian government has waived duties on maize imports to
encourage commercial imports, and advised farmers to plant drought
resistant and early maturing crops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Beats Canada to Win World Junior Hockey Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Russia defeated Canada 3-2 and
won the gold at the world junior hockey championship in Winnipeg
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
This was the second time in seven years that Russia grabbed
the gold of the world junior hockey tournament.
</P>
<P>
During Tuesday's game, the Russians dominated over their
Canadian counterpart from the beginning right to the end.
</P>
<P>
Russian player Artem Tschoubarov opened the scoring near the
end of the first period.
</P>
<P>
Canada tied the score 1-1 in the first half of the second
period, but was left behind after Russia scored in the second
half of the period.
</P>
<P>
In a power play of the third period, Canada scored for the
second time, thus tied the score 2-2 and forced an overtime.
</P>
<P>
It was Russian player Tschoubarov who brought an end to the
match, when he scored for the second time of the night, 5:13 into
the overtime.
</P>
<P>
To the disappointment of thousands of Canadian hockey fans,
Canada's hope to regain the title of world championship once
again fell apart.
</P>
<P>
However, it was a great improvement from last year, when
Canada was placed eighth at the tournament.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, Slovakia beat Sweden 5-4 and won the bronze
medal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vegetables in Beijing Now Fresher, But More Expensive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Most Beijing residents say they
are satisfied with the variety of vegetables now available in the
marketplace, but think that prices are a bit on the expensive
side, China Economic Times recently reported.
</P>
<P>
The paper says that this comes from a recent survey done by
the Horison Market Research Company, China Central Television,
and the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences' Physiology Research
Institute. The 400 people surveyed ranged in age from 18 to 65.
</P>
<P>
It found that older people have a higher opinion of the
availability of vegetables and that those from 56 to 65 years old
are the most content. Only 11 percent think the prices of
vegetables are "low", and 1.2 percent, that they are "very low."
</P>
<P>
The survey found that price is only the second most important
consideration, and that freshness is what they care most about,
with 47.1 percent saying that freshness is a priority; whereas
price was most important for only 28.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The researchers also found that the tendency to bargain is not
related to sex, but rather to the age and the economic condition
of the buyer. People who sell vegetables on the open market,
where most people shop, usually set their prices to allow some
room for bargaining.
</P>
<P>
People between the ages of 18 and 35 either never bargain or
seldom do so, while older people tend to do so more, and, the
higher their incomes, the less likely they are to bargain.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts say that Beijing residents are among the least
likely to bargin, while people in the South are more
price-conscious, and they attribute this to both natural and
social factors.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 07:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 6 (Xinhua) - The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post
</P>
<P>
-- Israel's expansion of settlements and suspension of the Wye
agreement have left the Palestinian National Authority with no
alternative but to proceed with the declaration of an independent
Palestinian state on May 4, PNA Planning Minister Nabil Sha'ath
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz
</P>
<P>
-- Former Chief of Staff Amnon Lipkin-Shahak is expected to
announce his candidacy for prime minister Wednesday as the head of
a new central party, the third of its kind in the country. He
emphasizes that he is not in the right nor the left, but in the
center, and that he aspires to solve the country's problems
through negotiations and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot
</P>
<P>
-- Shahak is reportedly in favor of a compromise with Syria
over the Golan Heights and is opposed to a unilateral withdrawal
from south Lebanon. He insists that the difference between the
ultra-religious and the secular should be resolved through direct
talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
