<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commercial Ship Abducted in S. Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, January 6 (Xinhua) -- A large commercial ferry transporting
miscellaneous goods was abducted by Somali gunmen Tuesday off the coast of
southern port town of Kismayu.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here Wednesday said the vessel which sailed from the
port of Dar es Salaam on its way to India faced technical difficulties off
Somalia's shores very close to its sea border with Kenya two days ago.
</P>
<P>
According to the VHF radio reports in Kismayu, 500 km south of the
capital Mogadishu, the vessel was then brought forcefully to the natural
port of Bur Gabo village along the coast, a few kilometers south of Kismayu.
</P>
<P>
The vessel called Johana is also carrying 21 crew member mainly
Africans and Indians with a few Turkish and Greeks. Unconfirmed reports
said the ferry is transporting commercial goods worth a few million U.S.
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gunman holding the vessel who belong to the Islamic fundamentalist
group of Al-Itihad Al-Islam said they brought all crew members down from
the ship to the village where they are being fed and treated well.
</P>
<P>
Ali Mohamed Ahmed who spoke for the Al-Itihad Al-Islam in Kismayu said
they are setting no conditions for the release of the ship and its crew
members. However, he said they will be asking the owners of the vessel to
reimburse them for the money they had spent for the services they have
rendered to the crew of the ship during their stay with them.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed who did not disclose how much money is involved in this
business also noted that they have tried to assist the ship technically,
but lack of spare parts made their efforts fruitless. It is known that
the Al- Itihad men will not at least loot the vessel, no matter how much
money they demand for release of the ship.
</P>
<P>
 This is the first time that a vessel is kidnapped in the southern
region of Lower Jubba by Somali gunmen. An Italian owned vessel, but
registered in Mombasa of Kenya is still being held in the coastal town of
Eyl of the northeast. A local court has fined the vessel for conducting
illegal fishing in Somali waters late last month.
</P>
<P>
The court had ordered the ship to pay 400,000 U.S. Dollars while its
Italian captain and his 32 crew members are fined a total of 100,000
Dollars after which they can still be substituted with a long term sentence.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
