<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 07:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Calls on Pakistan to Encounter Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Iran has called on Pakistan to
seriously confront the menace of terrorism and put the murderers
of Iranian citizens assassinated in that country on trial.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi issued
the call Tuesday during the three-day talks between Pakistani
Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad Khan and Iranian officials, the
Islamic Republic News Agency IRNA reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A number of Iranian citizens have been murdered by
unidentified assailants in Pakistan during the past few
years. Tehran has been urging Islamabad to identify and bring the
criminals to justice.
</P>
<P>
Asefi told IRNA that Ahmad Khan praised Iran's self-restraint
in the wake of the recent developments and promised that Pakistan
would follow up the murder cases and punish the assassins quickly.
</P>
<P>
He said that both sides in the talks underlined the necessity
of strengthening bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian side described the practical and serious measures
taken by Pakistan to remove misunderstandings as a preface to
boost Tehran-Islamabad ties and considered it as a ground for
future visits to Pakistan of ranking Iranian officials, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Asefi said that no date has been fixed for a visit by Iranian
Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi to Islamabad after his Pakistani
counterpart Sartaj Aziz extended his invitation to Kharrazi.
</P>
<P>
He said that Ahmad Khan and Iranian officials also discussed
Tehran-Islamabad cooperation in economic, cultural and mass media
fields and it was decided that Islamabad would make new studies on
purchase of oil from Iran and the construction of a joint refinery
in that country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
