<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Dismisses US Demand to Specify Nuclear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government
dismissed as inconsequential the demand by the United States to
spell out its need for the minimum nuclear deterrence, the
Hindustan Times reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Press Trust of India (PTI) here
Tuesday, the United States Ambassador to India Richard F. Celeste
asked India to specify in "concrete terms" its requirements of
nuclear deterrence so that it is not seen as an "open-ended
threat" to its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The Hindustan Times quoted sources in the Ministry of External
Affairs as saying Tuesday that India had already clarified its
position on the U.S. demand in one of the earlier rounds of talks
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman for the ministry referred to a recent print media
interview in which External Affairs Minister Jaswant Singh said
"the minimum nuclear deterrent is not a fixity".
</P>
<P>
Informed circles here expressed surprise over the revival of
the U.S. demand on the eve of a scheduled new round of talks here
later this month between Jaswant Singh and U.S. Deputy Secretary
of State Strobe Talbott on nuclear-related issues.
</P>
<P>
In the interview with PTI, Celeste said India's nuclear tests
last May "marked a kind of punctuation point" in relations between
Washington and New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
"Some expression of what India really wants and needs and
strives to achieve in a reasonably specific time, not specific in
numbers, but a range, is important to not only helping the U.S.
understand but also specific neighbors to understand....So that
there isn't an open-ended threat," Celeste said.
</P>
<P>
Celeste said the Indian government should make it clear as to
"how many missile systems and warheads does India need to have a
minimum nuclear deterrent".
</P>
<P>
The American envoy felt it was a transition period for
Indo-U.S. relations in 1998 which he termed as a "difficult year".
</P>
<P>
No tangible results were made in the previous rounds of talks
between the two countries in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
