<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Sets Targets to Reduce youth Suicides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand Ministry of
Health has set targets to reduce the suicide rates to 30 for every
100,000 young men from the current 37.8 and five for every
100,000 young women from the current 13.9 in the next seven years.
</P>
<P>
According to a latest ministry's report, the rate of suicide
among people aged 15 to 24 has not been improving in recent years
and suicide causes an average of 138 deaths a year in that age
group.
</P>
<P>
Although the male suicide rate has stabilized during the 1990s,
the female suicide rate has been rising since 1993, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, psychiatric problems, especially
depression, antisocial disorders and alcohol or drug abuse, are
major risk factors, with research showing that 90 percent of young
New Zealanders committing suicide have at least one mental
disorder.
</P>
<P>
The worsening suicide rates suggest that mental health
promotion needs improvement, the report said.
</P>
<P>
But other suicide risk factors include poor childhood
circumstances such as poor parenting and sexual abuse, poor
educational qualifications and low income, it added.
</P>
<P>
The targets for cutting the youth suicide rate should be
"challenging" because of its importance, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
