<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, January 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM -- Denmark's oil output in 1998 was up 3 percent
from the previous year to an all-time high of annual 11.8 million
metric tons, said reports reaching here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Danish officials were quoted as saying that the increase,
from the state-owned oil field in the North Sea, was the result
of applying new technologies on existing wells, rather than
expanded operations. (Denmark-Oil Output)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PRAGUE -- The Czech Republic suffered serious financial
difficulties in 1998 with its budget deficits hitting a record
high of 26.3 billion krone (about 877 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Czech Ministry of Finance said here on
Tuesday that the country failed to fulfill its budget-balancing
program for 1998, which set both revenues and expenditures at
536.6 billion krone (about 17.88 billion U.S. dollars). (Czech
Republic-Trade Deficit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- Germany's economy is in for a big slowdown in 1999,
with the world's financial and currency turbulence expected to
hurt exports and overall growth, according to a report of the DIW
economic research institute Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The DIW, one of the country's leading independent economic
research institute, said economic growth would reach only 1.4 per
cent this year. This figure was only about half the 1998 rate.
(Germany-Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The European Commission launched a program on
Tuesday to borrow two billion euros (2.36 billion U.S. dollars)
so as to issue euro-denominated bonds.
</P>
<P>
The program, encouraged by the impressive increase in the
1998 market for euro-denominated bonds both public and private
and both European and non-European, was signed by European
Finance Commissioner Yves-Thibault de Silguy and 12 large
international banks and financial institutions. (EU-Borrowing
Program)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Stock prices continued dropping in Tokyo Tuesday,
dragged down by the Japanese yen's further appreciation against
the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 183.15 points, or 1.37
percent, from Monday's close to end at 13,232.74. (Tokyo-Stock)
</P>
</TEXT>
