<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Plans to Close More U.S. Military Bases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
will ask Congress for permission to close more U.S. military
bases to help defray the cost of a major increase in U.S. defense
spending, a White House official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We continue to believe that we need authority from Congress
-- legislative authority -- to conduct two additional base
closing rounds," said Bob Bell, special assistant to the
president for national security affairs.
</P>
<P>
Bell said the administration wanted authority to start closing
bases from fiscal year 2001, which begins on October 1, 2000, and
estimated this would save "several billion" U.S. dollars during
the military's six-year budget window through 2005.
</P>
<P>
The request, which will be sent to Republican-held Congress on
February 1 as part of Clinton's new budget, would be the first
major increase in U.S. defense spending in a decade.
</P>
<P>
Closing military bases is highly unpopular in Congress, where
legislators are reluctant to antagonize the constituents who suffe
r when military facilities are shut down.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Defense Secretary William Cohen tried
unsuccessfully to win congressional authority for base closings
in 2001 and 2005.
</P>
<P>
Bell said Congress's refusal in recent years to allow the
Pentagon to close more bases is among the key reasons for a
decline in the readiness of some U.S. military units.
</P>
<P>
"In the longer term, of course, the savings would be much,
much greater," Bell added, saying it takes several years for the
lion's share of the savings to be realized.
</P>
<P>
As part of the administration's lobbying effort to get the new
military spending, the chiefs of U.S. military services on
Tuesday urged Congress to approve the money, saying it was the
minimum needed to keep troops and equipment ready for battle.
</P>
<P>
The heads of the Army, Air Force, Navy and Marine Corps all
said they would favor closing more U.S. military bases to help
pay for increased modernization and readiness.
</P>
<P>
On January 2, Clinton said he would ask Congress for an
additional 12 billion dollars in defense spending next year as
the first part of a six-year, 110 billion dollars drive to
sharpen the readiness of the military. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
