<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Sanction Micro-credit for Marginal Weavers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- A micro-credit of 200 million taka
(about 4.12 million U.S. dollars) is going to be sanctioned soon
for the country's marginal weavers for the current 1998-99 fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
"The credit program has already been recommended by the
Planning Commission and it is expected to be approved by the
Ministry of Finance shortly," A.K.M. Enayet Ullah, Bangladesh
Handloom board chairman, was quoted by The Financial Express daily
Wednesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
The credit was part of a 500-million-taka (about 10.31 million
dollars) credit program for the weavers, which was approved by the
Executive Committee for National Economic Council on November 4
last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The project was aimed at providing working capital to the
marginal weavers with a view to keeping the country's handlooms
operational, boosting the country's handloom fabrics, ensuring
employment opportunities and improving the socio-economic lives of
the poor weavers.
</P>
<P>
In the first phase, the project would be implemented on an
experimental basis for two years from July 1998 to June 2000, and
the next program would be undertaken on the basis of the two
years' performance.
</P>
<P>
Some 41,267 handloom units were expected to come under the
credit program in the first phase.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest survey by the Bureau of Statistics,
some 184,808 handloom units out of a total 501,834 in the country
had to be closed down due to lack of necessary working capital.
</P>
<P>
And a large number of the 317,026 handlooms in operation was
facing closure due to lack of working capital and other logistic
support.
</P>
<P>
The weavers, having one to five handloom units, would be
organized through groups for disbursing loans. They would have to
deposit 10 taka (about 20.6 U.S. cents) a week in their savings
accounts and would be selected for the loans with their saving
performance of minimum 12 weeks.
</P>
<P>
The interest rate against the loans was fixed at 10 percent a
year, and the weavers would have to repay the loan in some 36
installments in three years.
</P>
<P>
The total demand for loan was estimated at 3.14 billion taka
(about 67.74 million dollars) in the country's handloom sector,
the survey said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
