<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Tightens Campaign to Fight Against Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam detected a total of 9,000
incidents of drug smuggling and trafficking in 1998, the Vietnam
news agency reported Wednesday, quoting police sources.
</P>
<P>
Director of the Public Security Ministry's drug control
department Truong Huu Quoc said public security forces confiscated
1,135 kg of opium, 60,000 opium doses, 56.57 kg of heroin and
103,000 doses of other narcotics.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 398 kg of cannabis were confiscated.
</P>
<P>
The police also arrested 18,000 people for illicit drug
activities, including 21 foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The number of detections was 35 percent higher than 1997 while
those subject to litigation increased by 142.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Forty-nine of those to stand trial had been sentenced to death.
another 31 were sent to jail for life.
</P>
<P>
The senior police officer said Vietnam has 80,000 heavily
addicted drug users. Seventy percent of them are youth, including
1,500 secondary school students.
</P>
<P>
The number of heroin users continues to increase while the
number of recidivist drug addicts is not in decline.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese communist party chief Le Kha Phieu has asked the
public security forces to cooperate with all related organizations
to launch a campaign in the entire nation to fight drug abuse and
help users return to community life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
