<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Rules out Republic in Time for Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Australian federal
government Wednesday ruled out an Australian republic in time for
the Sydney 2000 Olympics, backing the prime minister as the person
to open the Games.
</P>
<P>
Acting Prime Minister Tim Fischer dismissed opposition calls
for the government to speed up the republic process so an
Australian president could open the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
The government will hold a referendum on a republic in November
and, if successful, Australia will become a republic in 2001,
months after the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Fischer strongly backed Prime Minister John Howard, who has
renewed his push to open the Games.
</P>
<P>
"On the question of who opens, well it should be the prime
minister of the day," Fischer told the Australian Broadcasting
Corporation News Radio.
</P>
<P>
Fischer rejected suggestions Howard's partisan post should
preclude him from opening the Games.
</P>
<P>
"The prime minister of the country is in this sense the
equivalent to the President of the U.S.A., and Ronald Reagan, Bill
Clinton, both very partisan, one Republican, one Democrat, opened
their respective Olympics," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is quite properly the role of the prime minister and we
should not get tangled up with the timing of important
constitutional change.
</P>
<P>
"A country does not change the timing of its constitutional
change to fit into the program and timetable of a particular,
albeit very major sporting event, the Olympics."
</P>
<P>
Australian Federal Opposition Leader Kim Beazley wants the job
to go to Governor-General Sir William Deane or if Australia
becomes a republic before the Games, to the Australian president.
</P>
<P>
"It is common knowledge that the office of prime minister in
this country is a partisan one," Beazley said.
</P>
<P>
Beazley said if the referendum voted for the republic there
would be time for an Australian republic to be established in time
for the Games.
</P>
<P>
If the referendum voted down the republic, the appropriate
person to open the Olympics Games would be the Governor-General,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Australia has virtually ruled out any possibility of the Queen
opening the Olympics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
