<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Spate of Bombings Alerts Thais </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Thailand's Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai has issued orders to
protect people's lives and property and ensure social stability.
</P>
<P>
Major newspapers quoted intelligence reports as saying that the
series of bombings might be politically motivated and intended to
discredit the government and cause damage rather than take lives.
</P>
<P>
Chuan said: "According to the assessment of some intelligence
officials, the recent incidents could be aimed at creating
confusion to a point the government can no longer maintain peace."
</P>
<P>
But government officials refused to say who could be behind
the attacks. "I think they are not ordinary people but specialists
in explosives," Chuan noted.
</P>
<P>
A blast went off during the December 6-20 Asian Games, damaging
the Democracy Monument in downtown Bangkok. On the New Year's eve,
a bomb struck a police station, devastating its parking lot. An
explosion was also reported at the site of the residence of Chiang
Mai's prison warden early on Monday. Leaflets criticizing the
government were found on the scene. Also on Monday police defused
a bomb at a condominium in downtown Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
Because of the bombings, some nightspots were deserted and
patrons were scared away, raising fears that the tourism industry
might be affected.
</P>
<P>
Police sources said leading figures in certain political groups
were suspected of involvement in some of the bombings and were
being watched.
</P>
<P>
The army and police were also carrying out internal
investigations into their own personnel that were suspected of
having a hand in the bombings. Press reports linked the police
station blast to a row among senior police officers who could not
agreed on the share of interests from an entertainment complex.
</P>
<P>
As part of security measures, army-police units have stepped up
routine patrols to prevent military personnel from moonlighting as
guards. The army is also taking measures to weed out unruly
officers from entertainment areas, press reports said.
</P>
<P>
But the army denied that military personnel were engaged in the
bombings. Earlier, Wattanachai Wuttisiri, deputy defense minister,
urged the media to stop speculating, saying it would only cause
confusion. But He pledged to cooperate with investigators in
bringing to justice any officers involved.
</P>
<P>
Pol Maj-Gen Pitthaya Charoenpanit, deputy commissioner of the
Metropolitan Police, said he had ruled out all non-political
motives in the police station blast.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that there were conflicts between two senior
officers at the station but did not think they would have launched
the attack.
</P>
<P>
"They would know that they would come under close observation
or even under investigation if they did do it," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think the blast can be blamed on mafiosi either,
because they know their own interests will be damaged if the
situation escalates," he said.
</P>
<P>
Police and government seem to have a pat explanation for the
blast, the real motive of which will remain a mystery, said a
source close to the investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
