<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru's Fish Exports Decline Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Peru's fish exports last year fell
from 1.4 billion U.S. dollars to 580 million dollars, the
Association of National Fisheries reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Four major fish products were particularly affected, said the
association.
</P>
<P>
Exports of fish powder amounted to 330 million dollars, while
fish oil reached 18 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
In addition, exports of tinned and frozen fish were
respectively 39 million and 180 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The association attributed the slump to the El Nino
phenomenon, which resulted in fewer fish in Peruvian waters.
</P>
<P>
The country's catch of fish last year was 4.1 million tons,
down 47 percent from 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, the association predicted the fish catch and exports
would rise again this year.
</P>
<P>
The catch and exports are expected to reach 6.6 million tons
and 930 million dollars respectively. 
</P>
