<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia's Top Kosovo Official Raps OSCE Observers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia's top
administrative official in charge of Kosovo Veljko Odalovic
alleged that observers of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) did not honor their obligations.
</P>
<P>
Odalovic was quoted by a Tanjug news agency report Tuesday as
telling the Italian newspaper La Repubblica that OSCE observers
in Serbia's southern province of Kosovo were not serious in doing
their job.
</P>
<P>
As provided by the agreement signed last October by
Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic and U.S. envoy Richard
Holbrooke, the observers have the mandate to oversee a cease-fire
between Serb security forces and militant ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
According to Odalovic, Yugoslavia had observed the document
thoroughly by pulling its special forces out from Kosovo,
allowing NATO aircraft to fly monitoring missions over the area,
and working closely with international humanitarian groups.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, militant ethnic Albanians in Kosovo since
have launched over 400 attacks on Serb police and civilians,
killing more than 40 of them and driving many Serbian and
Montenegrin residents out from their homes in about a dozen
villages.
</P>
<P>
Besides blaming OSCE observers for inaction in stopping the
attacks, Odalovic said the OSCE personnel also forgot that the
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia "is a sovereign state" and "has
the right to defend its borders." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
