<HEADLINE> Primary Education Reforms to Take Shape in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Reforms in primary education are
scheduled to be initiated in Sri Lanka from January 8, which will
affect primary schools islandwide.
</P>
<P>
These reforms are based on the recommendations made by the
Presidential Task Force on General Education, the Island newspaper
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Through the revised curriculum pupils are expected to acquire
not only knowledge and skills but also develop hidden talents.
</P>
<P>
They will be encouraged to learn to think, be inquisitive and
ask questions, find answers, discover things and to be creative.
</P>
<P>
They are also expected to learn to have care and respect for
others, understand other points of view and grow up with
self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
The principal mode of learning will be guided-play with
secondary emphasis on activities and minimum of desk work.
</P>
<P>
The curriculum is organized under Language, Mathematics,
Religion and Environmental Studies.
</P>
<P>
English will be used in communication during activities and
play. Later English will be introduced as a separate subject in
addition to communication.
</P>
<P>
Other subjects such as natural science, health, creative
activity and aesthetic studies will be integrated under
environmental studies.
</P>
<P>
The curriculum is designed to develop competencies necessary
for living. 
</P>
</TEXT>
