<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Iraq Violates Agreement with United Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Tuesday that Iraq has violated an agreement with the United
Nations by refusing to give visas to some American and British
workers from U.N. humanitarian programs.
</P>
<P>
"The suggestion by the Iraqis that American and British
workers cannot be protected is a rationale we regard as phony, a
blatant attempt to violate U.N. principles and disrupt U.N.
operations," State Department spokesman James Rubin told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Iraq on Monday sent the United Nations a message saying it
could no longer guarantee the safety of some U.S. and British
workers involved in U.N. humanitarian programs after the two
countries bombed Iraq, which resulted in the deaths of nearly 100
Iraqi lives.
</P>
<P>
The message listed one American and 13 Britons who would not
get their visas renewed or would have to leave when their
contracts for U.N. "oil-for-food" humanitarian programs expired.
</P>
<P>
Rubin declined to say what the United States would do if Iraq
persisted in excluding some Americans from the U.N. humanitarian
programs.
</P>
<P>
"What we can do is show that we're going the extra mile by
providing funds, assistance, expertise, and equipment to the
effort to help feed, clothe and provide medicine," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
