<HEADLINE> Thailand Not to Sacrifice National Interests For WTO Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Supachai is one of the four major contenders bidding for the
post of WTO director general. The WTO Council will try to decide
this month who will replace current WTO chief Renato Ruggiero who
is scheduled to leave at the end of April. Thailand is hoping that
the United States, which has been tightlipped, will back Supachai.
</P>
<P>
The sources on Tuesday quoted Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
as saying Thailand would not offer anything in return for support
from the United States. Chuan would send a second letter to U.S.
President Bill Clinton to sound out the U.S. position, according
to the sources.
</P>
<P>
Despite mounting pressure among the 132 members of the world's
largest trading group to quickly decide which candidate should
take over the WTO post, the final decision may be further delayed
as the United States and European Union have not decided whom they
will support.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Foreign Ministry has convinced diplomats from
France, Portugal, Greece and Spain, and would try to do the same
with envoys from Austria, Italy, Chile, Pakistan, Germany,
Colombia, South Africa, Sweden and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan said earlier that he was
confident Supachai's portfolio would impress the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Supachai is seen as a bridge between the developed and
developing countries because he has seen Thailand in crisis and
has implemented part of the reform process which is based on the
country's continued commitment to open trade.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. may not feel comfortable with the idea of a new chief
from a developing country leading world trade, analysts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
