<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Myanmar Makes Progress in Fight Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar continued its efforts in
drug eradication in 1998 and made progress.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of 1998, a nation-wide campaign to collect
baseline data on poppy cultivation and drug addicts was launched
with an aim of making correct assessment on the actual opium yield
and the number of drug addicts in the country.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that in the country there were 61,236
hectares of poppy cultivation that would yield 665.28 tons raw
opium and could be refined into 66.52 tons of heroin. Total drug
addicts reportedly reached 66,463.
</P>
<P>
In February, Myanmar ceremonially burnt down for the 12th time
in Yangon a total of 5,759 kg of seized narcotic drugs including
898 kg of heroin, 4,587 kg of opium and 2.84 million stimulant
tablets.
</P>
<P>
In the same month, experts of Myanmar and the United States
carried out poppy yield surveys in the country's Shan state for
the fourth time since 1993 under the two countries' anti-drug
program.
</P>
<P>
In March, a mission of the United Nations Drug Control Program
(UNDCP) visited Yangon and worked with Myanmar officials to draft
a 10-year project for the elimination of poppy cultivation and
development of opium substitute undertakings in the country.
</P>
<P>
Of the four UNDCP integrated rural development projects in
Myanmar, three have been completed and the remaining one is under
implementation.
</P>
<P>
In the same month, a 21-country regional seminar on alternative
development for poppy cultivation was held in Yangon with Japan's
financial support to exchange information and experiences in the
fight against drugs.
</P>
<P>
In July, a national training workshop under a six-country
(China, Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar, Thailand and Vietnam) memorandum
of understanding for sub-regional cooperation on drug control took
place in Yangon to strengthen the capacity of the signatories in
project design and management, following the work-out in Bangkok
in July 1997 of 11 projects on law enforcement, supply reduction
and demand reduction.
</P>
<P>
In December, the Kokang area in northern Shan state began
commercial production of buckwheat, a kind of opium-substitute
crop.  The formal launching of buckwheat production marked one of
Myanmar's achievements in its endeavor to eliminate drugs in the
year.
</P>
<P>
According to official estimation, in the 1998-99 fiscal year
which began in April, a total of over 5,898 hectares could be
placed under poppy substitution crops including paddy, corn,
sugarcane and Japanese buckwheat.
</P>
<P>
It is further estimated that a total of 4,916 hectares could
also be put under other substitute crops in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
Besides in the first six months of 1998, Myanmar seized a total
of 4,927 kilograms of narcotics including 219 kg of heroin and
4,471 kg of opium, destroying 15 heroin refineries and 8,000
hectares of poppy plantations.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has laid down two strategies of eradication of narcotic
drugs -- designating drug eradication and prevention activities as
a national duty and gradual elimination of poppy cultivation by
promoting the standard of living of the national races.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has vowed to totally eliminate poppy cultivation in 15
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
