<HEADLINE> Thailand to Issue 500m U.S. Dollars in Samurai Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Thailand plans to issue 500
Million U.S. dollars in Samurai bonds by March to be insured by
the Japanese government as part of its bail-out plan for regional
economies, the Bangkok Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda was quoted as saying
that the bonds would be issued by the Petroleum Authority of
Thailand and the Electricity Generating Authority of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The 10-year bonds would be guaranteed by the Finance Ministry
and denominated in yen. After the issue, funds raised would be
swapped for U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin said the Japanese Ministry of Trade and Industry would
provide credit insurance for the bond issues, which would be
privately placed in the Tokyo market.
</P>
<P>
Japanese officials are selecting underwriters for the bonds.
</P>
<P>
The plan offers 30 billion U.S. dollars in financial aid to
crisis-stricken Asian countries. South Korea, Malaysia and
Indonesia have signaled interest borrowing from the program.
</P>
<P>
Japan had earlier approved 1.85 Billion U.S. dollars in
assistance through the plan for Thailand in the form of medium-and
long-term loans from Japanese Export-Import Bank and Japan's
Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund. The fund will be used to
support industry development and social welfare program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
