<HEADLINE> Czech Republic's Budget Deficits Record High in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Officials from the Czech Ministry of Finance said here on
Tuesday that the country failed to fulfill its budget-balancing
program for 1998, which set both revenues and expenditures at
536.6 billion krone (about 17.88 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Instead, as economic experts here pointed out, the Czech finan
cial condition had one of its worst years in 1998, with revenues
totaling 537.5 billion Krone (about 17.92 billion U.S. dollars)
and expenditures 563.8 billion krone (18.79 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic enjoyed a short-lived financial soundness
following the adoption of the market economy. In 1994 and 1995,
the country recorded a financial surplus of 10.4 billion krone (
about 347 million dollars) and 7.3 billion krone (243 million
dollars) respectively.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Czech's budget failed to strike a balance as an
economic downturn set in. Financial deficits in that year totaled
1.6 billion krone (53 million dollars). The figure rose to 15.7
billion krone (523 dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The parliament of the Czech Republic recently endorsed a finan
cial budget for 1999 with a deficit of 31 billion krone (1.03
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
To make up the huge deficits, the country has taken to issuing
national debt bonds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
