<HEADLINE> Indonesian Capital Market Reacts Positively to new </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's local bourse reacted
positively to the 1999/2000 zero-growth State Budget announced
Tuesday by President B.J. Habibie, with blue chips gaining ground
in moderate trading.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah (national currency) also perked up on news of the
conservative budget, rising to 7,825 against the U.S. dollar from
7,925 at the close of the previous day's trading, dealers said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The new budget, unveiled by the president, is balanced at 218.2
trillion rupiah (about 29 billion U.S. dollars), 17.3 percent
decline over that of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The budget assumes zero economic growth, 17 percent inflation
and a rupiah-U.S. dollar exchange rate of 7,500 rupiah, which
Habibie considered a reflection of positive economic developments
in recent months.
</P>
<P>
The present budget, which ends March 31 1999, assumed economic
contraction of minus 12 percent, inflation of 77.63 percent and a
10,600-rupiah per dollar exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
At the closing trading Tuesday, share prices surged through the
key 400-point level, ending 3.6 percent firmer as investors bought
shares across the board.
</P>
<P>
"The market believed that all the macroeconomic assumptions in
the 1999/2000 State Budget seemed realistic," a chief dealer with
a joint venture bank said.
</P>
<P>
Money market dealers said the rupiah, which opened at
7,925/7,950 per dollar, was dull in the morning trading session,
but ultimately strengthened.
</P>
<P>
They said the rupiah's gain could also be attributed to the
27-month high of the Japanese yen to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Taking their lead from the rupiah, share prices on the Jakarta
Stock Exchange soared, with the main bench-mark price index rising
14.24 points to 408.70 on the total turnover of 221 million shares
valued at 191.47 billion rupiah (24.54 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Stock analysts and brokers said the market was bullish on
Tuesday because the budget's macroeconomic assumptions were in
line with the country's dire economic condition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
