<HEADLINE> Gansu Bans Illegal Coal Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Gansu Province
has launched a campaign to rectify the local coal mining industry,
with hundreds of illegal small mines subject to closure.
</P>
<P>
Official figures indicate that Gansu has 1,374 coal coal mines,
of them 1,300 being small ones.
</P>
<P>
Mines operating without permits or production certificates, as
well as those failing to meet environmental protection standards
will be closed, according to a provincial official.
</P>
<P>
He noted that at least 523 coal mines are subject to closure.
</P>
<P>
"Most small mines are poorly equipped and lack the technology
to guarantee safe production," the official said.
</P>
<P>
He said small mines not only waste resources, prone to
accidents and create pollution, but also adversely impact the
normal order of the coal market. He cited the aforementioned
factors as the reason for the current coal inventory of 2.2
million tons. 
