<HEADLINE> Thailand's Exports to Grow 3 Percent This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The Department of Business
Economics of the Thai Commerce Ministry believes the value of
Thailand's exports will grow by 3 percent this year from an
estimated 54 billion U.S. dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The revival of local financial institutions, a stable baht and
improved efficiency by exporters were behind the optimistic
forecast, Karun Kittisataporn, director-general of the department
was quoted Wednesday by the Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
As government measures to reform the domestic financial sector
bear fruit, local lenders are expected to resume extending credit
to exporters. As well, the stability of the baht would improve
Thai exporters' confidence in entering new transactions with
foreigners, he said.
</P>
<P>
Many exporters postponed transactions in 1998 because of
fluctuations in the value of the baht, especially in the first
half of the year. Changes of one or two baht to the dollar in a
single day made it very difficult for exporters to calculate costs
and prices.
</P>
<P>
The estimated 54 billion U.S. dollars value of exports in 1998
was six percent lower than in the previous year, but the
department was sticking with its forecast of 3 percent growth for
this year.
</P>
<P>
In the first 10 months of 1998, exports in dollar terms were a
6.4-percent decline to 45.27 billion U.S. dollars. Exports in
October alone were down by 12.7 percent from the same month of
1997 to 4.63 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
