<HEADLINE> Indonesia Cuts Sports Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Prospects for Indonesian
sports this year include a potentially desperate struggle to meet
financial needs after the government has slashed the yearly
budget allocation to 60.6 billion rupiah (8 million U.S.
dollars) from 86.7 billion rupiah last year.
</P>
<P>
The fate of sports in the Southeast Asian country was sealed
here on Tuesday with President B.J Habibie's announcement of the
national budget, which has also seen an overall reduction of 17.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
"This is of course not good news for the Indonesian sports
community. And it was far from a respite for us in the wake of
the upcoming Southeast Asian Games and Sydney Olympics," said
Minister of Sports and Youth Affairs Agung Laksono in response to
the announcement.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister was apparently trying to brave the
stingy financial budget by saying that he remained optimistic
about prospects.
</P>
<P>
"We must be thinking positively about the next challenges. We
should all exert everything we can to do the best we can," he was
quoted by the Indonesian Observer Wednesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, which has just arrived back from the Bangkok Asian
Games last December, will be competing in the 20th Southeast
Asian Games in Brunei this August before preparing for another, e
ven tougher event in when the Olympics are held in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
"We need as much as between 100 billion rupiah to 150 billion
rupiah every year including financial assistance for KONI
(Indonesian Sports Council)," he added.
</P>
<P>
The daunting shortage of funds will certainly leave the sports
world highly dependent on business entities, which have so far
traditionally borne the brunt of the financial backup.
</P>
<P>
Despite the lack of funds, the minister both Southeast Asian
Games and the Sydney Olympics should be the country's priority.
</P>
<P>
"Otherwise, we would seem to be curtailing potential
athletes," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister also did not see the reduction as a serious
threat to sports development in the country, as the government
has offset the financial aid to be given directly to the
provincial administrations.
</P>
<P>
The bailout, which is not included in the budget, earmarked
athlete scouting and the provision of sport facilities at the
provincial and regency levels. 
</P>
