<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Asian Airlines' Bumpy Road to Rehabilitation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At the same time, air crashes, which have claimed four times as
many as lives in Asia as the rest of the world in the past 18
months, cast a shadow on increase in traffic volume.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 1,000 people have died in major airline accidents in
Asia in the past 18 months, one of the region's worst periods in
aviation.
</P>
<P>
Partly because of the financial crisis, and partly because of
the air safety problem, growth of traffic volume in the region
slowed down to about 4 percent in the 1997-98 fiscal year from 8-9
percent before the crisis.
</P>
<P>
To tide over the crisis, Asian airlines have undertaken
restructuring programs. The AAPA said that a number of its members
have either deferred or canceled their aircraft orders, while
others sold their planes to co-members.
</P>
<P>
Garuda Indonesia is undergoing a restructuring program with a
leaner fleet of 45 aircraft, from the original 57 planes, by this
year.
</P>
<P>
Apart from reducing capacity, several AAPA members have
undergoing route restructuring programs.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's Asiana Airlines and Korean Air discontinued their
Seoul-Europe and Guam-Spain passenger services. Other Asian
carriers, such as Ansett Australia, Air New Zealand and Qantas,
have dropped flights to South Korea at a short notice.
</P>
<P>
As part of their restructuring programs, some of the region's
major airlines have, or are considering joining one of the global
alliances, because alliances can help airlines reduce cost in the
shorter term by sharing facilities and staff, consolidating
suppliers and canceling redundant flights.
</P>
<P>
Cathay Pacific Airways has announced that it would become part
of the new "oneworld" alliance, comprising Cathay, British
Airways, American Airlines, Canadian Airlines and Qantas Airways.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Airlines has not disclosed its plan for joining an
alliance, but it has cooperative agreements with Lufthansa and Air
New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said there is a good possibility that Singapore
Airlines will join the Star Alliance, which has already included
United Airlines, Lufthansa, Air Canada and Thai Airways. And Air
New Zealand, Ansett International and Ansett Australia have
planned to join the alliance this month.
</P>
<P>
With all these rehabilitation measures in place, airline
officials estimated a recovery may still take two to three years,
and by then, traffic will growth by 5 percent a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke010604 - Feature: Asian Airlines' Bumpy Road to Rehabilitation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 6 (Xinhua) -- The temporary closure of the
Philippine Airlines (PAL), Asia's oldest airline, last September,
reflected the worst-case scenario for the region's carriers, which
struggled with the financial crisis in 1998.
</P>
<P>
For Asian airlines, the year 1999 could still be a very tough
one, as financial problems, lower traffic volume, and air safety
will make their road to rehabilitation very bumpy.
</P>
<P>
Take PAL as an example. Despite President Joseph Estrada's
promise that the government will rescue PAL at any cost, the
57-year-old airline would fold up again if it fails to find a
strategic partner in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
The government has made it clear that the state will not
provide any money to save PAL, and the airline has to find support
from the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Since it resumed domestic and international flights last
October, PAL has not found a way to make good on some 2.1 billion
U.S. dollars in debts, although its secret talks over a
partnership with the Hongkong-based Cathay Pacific Airways and the
U.S.-based Northwest are reportedly going on.
</P>
<P>
Financial difficulties, compounded by a series of labor
strikes, forced PAL to seek relief from payment of 2.1 billion
dollars in debts last June due to cash flow problems.
</P>
<P>
PAL registered a net loss of 6.1 billion pesos (153 million
dollars) in the first half of the 1997-98 fiscal year ended last
September, compared with a net loss of 2.1 billion pesos (52.7
million dollars) a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Just like PAL, many Asian airlines suffered financial loss in
1998. National flag carrier Malaysian Airline System posted a net
loss of 441.1 million ringgit (116.1 million dollars) for the
first half ended on September 30, compared with a net profit of
23.5 million ringgit (6.19 million dollars) a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Also, Singapore Airlines' net profit fell 24 percent in the
first half ended in September.
</P>
<P>
Based on figures from the Association of Asia-Pacific Airlines
(AAPA), which groups 19 carriers based in the region, combined
passenger revenue of members for the 1997-98 (October to
September) fiscal year slipped 4.5 percent to only 37.869 billion
dollars from 39.670 billion dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
What has caused the financial difficulties for Asian airlines?
</P>
<P>
The drop in value of some Asian currencies by 15 to 60 percent
against the dollar has caused immense difficulties for Asian
carriers, because dollars are the currency in which aircraft are
traded and aviation fuel is priced, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
During the year, the financial crisis has also forced many Asia
airlines to slash fare, abandon routes and cancel orders for new
aircraft as passengers have stopped flying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peruvian President Names New Premier As Economy Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian President Alberto
Fujimori said Tuesday that he has named Prime Minister Victor Joy
Way as finance minister to replace Jorge Baca Campodnico.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference, Fujimori said that Joy Way Rojas would
continue the free market policy which began in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori said that Baca's removal was part of a political bid
to set up a new ministerial team for the last one and half years
of his term which will end in July 2000.
</P>
<P>
The reshuffle was designed to create a ministerial team able
to inject new life into Peru's slump economy, Joy Way said.
</P>
<P>
In the broader cabinet reshuffling, nine other ministers were
also removed.
</P>
<P>
The four ministers who remain in office are Interior Minister
Jose Villanueva, Defense Minister Julio Salazar, Energy and Mines
Minister Daniel Hokama, and Foreign Minister Fernando de
Trazegnies.
</P>
<P>
Nine ministers, including those responsible for agriculture,
justice, health and industry, will be replaced and two others
rotated, he said.
</P>
<P>
Former Prime Minister Alberto Pandolfi will move to the
Transportation Ministry, replacing Antonio Paucar, who will move
to the Fisheries Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori ruled out any changes in the economic policy, but
added that some "adjustments" were possible in the future so that
"the program's benefits have concrete effects on the country's
microeconomy."
</P>
<P>
After growth of more than 7.4 percent in 1997, Peru's economy
grew by just an estimated 1.5 percent in 1998 due to the Asian
economic crisis and damage caused by the El Nino phenomenon,
which changed weather patterns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
