<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam, Laos Agree to Quicken Port Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam and Laos has agreed to
accelerate the ongoing construction of a sea port on Vietnam's
central coast and the route leading from the port to central Laos,
official reports here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement came at the 21st meeting of the Vietnam-Laos
Inter-Governmental Commission for Economic, Cultural, Scientific
and Technological Cooperation which was held here Tuesday on the
official visit by Lao President Khamtay Siphandone.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials of the two counties reviewed the work done in
1998 and discussed cooperation plans for 1999, which cover the
fields of trade, personnel training, agriculture, tourism,
transport and communications, and power.
</P>
<P>
On transport and communications, the two sides agreed to focus
their cooperation on major projects and programs, striving to
complete the construction of the Vung Ang port in Vietnam's
central province of Ha Tinh and the road linking this port with
Laos.
</P>
<P>
Both the projects are scheduled for completion by the year
2000. Then landlocked Laos will be able to use the route and the
port in Vietnam's Ha Tinh province to transport its shipments to
other countries.
</P>
<P>
This year, Vietnam will train 450 Lao students who major in
these fields and send between 20 and 25 Vietnamese students to
Laos.
</P>
<P>
According to leading press here, Vietnam's Prime Minister Phan
Van Khai told visiting Lao President Khamtay Siphandone that
"comprehensive cooperation between Vietnam and Laos would be
further developed, especially in economy, agriculture, industry,
energy and transport and communications."
</P>
<P>
The Lao top leader replied that "Laos and Vietnam should work
out a strategy for their long-term cooperation, particularly in
economy, agriculture, forestry and farm produce processing,
transport and communications and energy in order to better exploit
each country's potential and strength for their peoples' happiness
and prosperity."
</P>
<P>
Khamtay Siphandone arrived here Monday for a four-day official
visit to Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
