<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Loans Encourage Private Auto Ownership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Bank loans have resulted in
increasing private purchases of automobiles in Shanghai, China's
largest financial and economic center.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai branches of the Industrial and Commercial Bank of
China (ICBC) and the China Construction Bank (CCB) introduced auto
loans on October 13 last year.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai CCB branch has granted 130 automobile loans valued
at over 10 million yuan. In addition, the Shanghai Branch of ICBC,
China's largest bank, reports a contracted loan volume of 2.2
million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Shanghainese are enjoying constantly rising income levels which
have prompted an increasing number of people to purchase
automobiles. Nonetheless, the private ownership of automobiles has
grown slowly due to high licensing costs of 20,000 yuan, a
dramatic drop on the previous, amazingly high figure of 160,000
yuan each.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that Shanghai has a mere 8,000 private
automobiles, compared to 400,000 units in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The availability of automobile loans and constantly improving
road conditions will inevitably boost automobile sales, according
to local economists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
