<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile Earmarks 161 Million Dollars for Drought-Plagued Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Chile's agriculture minister
Carlos Mladinic on Tuesday said that the ministry will allocate
161.7 million U.S. dollars to help farmers affected by a one-year
drought.
</P>
<P>
Scarce rainfall made 1998 the third driest year in Chile in
this century, only surpassed by drought in 1924 and 1968.
</P>
<P>
The scarce rainfall came as a result of weather changes caused
by the periodic warming of tropical Pacific waters, a phenomenon
known as El Nino, which is followed by droughts caused by La Nina.
</P>
<P>
The drought forced the government to declare an agriculture
alert in 120 locations in an extensive area in the center of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Despite the authorities' claim that vegetable and fruit crops
will not be affected, farmers were warned that crops like wheat
and leguminous plants needing irrigation would be hurt.
</P>
<P>
The drought is also expected to affect electricity supplies
mainly generated by hydraulic power stations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
