<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0100 GMT, January 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. defense officials reported a new incident
in the no-fly zone over southern Iraq on Tuesday, saying none of
the U.S. warplanes involved in the incident were lost.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the U.S. Central Command, Major Joe LaMarca,
said further details are yet to be available as military experts
were still checking reports from the region.
</P>
<P>
Defense officials said no U.S. aircraft were lost. Two F-15s
and two F-14s from the Navy were involved in the confrontation.
(US-No-fly Zone Incident-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The European Commission on Tuesday confirmed its
suspension of a commission official for mishandling confidential
documents.
</P>
<P>
An unidentified man from the commission's financial control
department was suspended on December 16 last year for four months
and further discipline is pending on judicial investigation,
commission officials said. (Brussels-Suspension)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Customs officers of the Moscow Domodedovo Airport
on Monday seized 6 kilograms of heroin, the largest catch in five
years, Itar-Tass news agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Five Tajik nationals were arrested on suspicion that they
participated in trafficking the heroin, which had a street value
of more than 1 million U.S. dollars, Tass said, quoting a
spokesman for the State Customs Committee.
(Russia-Heroin-Seizure)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GENEVA -- The head of a United Nations agency on HIV/AIDS has
expressed his condolences to the family of a South African woman
beaten to death after she admitted she had HIV last December.
</P>
<P>
"It is with great sorrow that I learnt about the tragic death
of Ms Gugu Dlamini, a volunteer of the National Association of
People living with HIV/AIDS," said Peter Piot, Executive Director
of UNAIDS in a letter to South African Vice President Thabo
Mbeki. (SAfrica-Aids) 
</P>
