<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Firms Support Qingdao Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, January 6 (Xinhua) -- Large enterprises and groups are
becoming an increasingly important factor promoting economic
growth in Qingdao, a major port city of east China's Shandong
Province.
</P>
<P>
State-owned industrial enterprises and non-state firms with
annual sales of more than five million yuan each had a combined
industrial value-added of 22.5 billion yuan for the first 11 months
of 1998, up 16.5 percent on the 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
The total output of 88.7 billion yuan for related enterprises
between January-November represented an increase of 10.3 percent,
with the sales-to-production ratio hitting 96.5 percent for the
1998 period.
</P>
<P>
Qingdao has placed priority on development of the sectors of
biological engineering, electronic information, household electric
appliances, shipping, vehicle manufacturing, food and beverage,
and power equipment over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
The city invested 6.6 billion yuan in industrial technological
renovations during 1998, with some 57 percent of the total going
to the top 10 enterprise groups.
</P>
<P>
Qingdao's technical renovation inputs are expected to total 15
billion yuan over a three-year period, according to a municipal
official.
</P>
<P>
Analysts note that large enterprises made extremely important
contributions to the rapid expansion of Qingdao's industrial
sector in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Total industrial production for the Haier and Hisense groups,
two group companies which account for one fourth of the city's total
economy, surged 82 percent and 44.9 percent respectively during
the first 11 months of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
