<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian PM Foresees Success of Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Massimo
D'Alema said Tuesday that he foresees the success of the euro,
the single European currency launched on January 1.
</P>
<P>
"No one could foresee how the euro would grow, but it's
success was predictable," D'Alema said in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
He said that this was can be seen from the fact the euroland's
currencies stayed unaffected by the Asian economic crisis last
year. The euro was successful "even before its birth," the
Italian prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of his recent private visit to the United States,
D'Alema said that there was initially some reservation vis-a-vis
the euro among Americans, but "now there is respect for the
European currency."
</P>
<P>
The Americans are calling it the "eurodollar," which is a sign
of respect for Europe's potential, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that when he saw how the European bourses in the
euro-area soared and when he read the negative data coming out of
the London stock exchange, he thought what would have happened to
Italy if the Italian lira had not managed to enter the euroland.
</P>
<P>
"We would have had a sense of defeat, of having been shunted
to the sidelines, and now it was a historic victory for Italy to
enter the euroland," D'Alema added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Players to Vote Wednesday on Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 5 (Xinhua) -- NBA players will have a
chance to decide on the league's final proposal Wednesday, and a
negative vote will likely prompt the cancellation of the entire
season -- a first in pro sports history.
</P>
<P>
NBA Commissioner David Stern rejected the final proposal from
the NBA union, which then decided to put the league's last
proposal to a vote.
</P>
<P>
Stern then reaffirmed that the nine-member labor relations
committee to the Board of Governors to vote to cancel the
remainder of the season on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
No talks are scheduled, which means the future of the season
--and perhaps the sport -- will come down to Wednesday's vote of
more than 400 players.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the union's 19-member negotiating committee
unanimously rejected the final proposal from the NBA, which Stern
mailed directly to each player.
</P>
<P>
Stern also indicated that in the absence of an agreement,
teams would be outfitted with replacement players for the
1999-2000 season. The declaration was designed to put pressure on
the players. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
