<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Heart Association Recommends Homocysteine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 5 (Xinhua) -- An American Heart
Association Science Advisory has urged doctors to begin screening
high-risk patients with a personal or family history of heart
disease for elevated homocysteine levels.
</P>
<P>
The advisory, carried on the current issue of the association's
weekly journal Circulation, comes in the wake of a number of
recent studies, including a 14-year study at the Harvard School of
Public Health involving 80,000 women, which concluded that high
homocysteine levels play a central role in cardiovascular disease.
</P>
<P>
At normal levels, homocysteine is an amino acid used by the
body to help build and maintain body tissue. Too much
homocysteine, however, causes blood patelets to clump together and
damage the lining of arteries.
</P>
<P>
Cardiovascular disease is the leading cause of death in the
United States, costing the country 150 billion U.S. dollars a
year. An estimated 20 million Americans, more than one of every
three people with heart disease, experience high levels of
homocysteine, according to the advisory. Screening for the problem
could significantly reduce the likelihood of heart attacks and
strokes among certain high-risk patients.
</P>
<P>
Elevated levels of homocysteine can be reduced with a change in
diet, the advisory said. Because high levels of homocysteine
directly correlate to low levels of folic acid and vitamins B12
and B6, in addition to screening, the advisory also urges all
Americans to increase their intake of foods containing folic acid
and vitamins B12 and B6 such as leafy green vegetables, fruits and
legumes.
</P>
<P>
It will probably soon be as common to have one's homocysteine
level checked as it is now to have one's cholesterol level
checked, the advisory said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
