<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1998 A Record Breaking Year for IPE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON January 5 (Xinhua) - Volumes of trade on the
International Petroleum Exchange's (IPE) futures and options
contracts in 1998 rose overall by almost a third to 19.4 million
contracts, the Exchange announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Last year was the most successful ever in the eighteen year
history of the IPE. This compares with 14.7 million contracts
traded in 1997, the IPE said.
</P>
<P>
Brent Crude futures made up 70 percent of the volume traded,
averaging just under 54,000 lots a day. This volume represents
about 54 million barrels of crude oil or just under three quarters
of total world daily oil production.
</P>
<P>
Over the year as a whole 13.6 million lots of Brent Crude were
traded, compared with 10.3 million lots the previous year, an
increase of 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
Gas Oil futures were up almost 25 percent on the previous year
at 5.0 million lots. Options on Brent Crude and Gas Oil traded
439,110 lots, up 40 percent on 1997.
</P>
<P>
The highest percentage increase was for Natural Gas futures.
1998 was the first full year of trading for the Natural Gas
contract, which was launched on 31 January 1997, according to the
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Lynton Jones, chief executive of the IPE said: "The
exceptionally low price levels in 1998 have clearly demonstrated
the value of hedging."
</P>
<P>
"The dramatic growth in the volumes we have traded in the year
indicate that people appreciate the range and quality of risk
management tools that we provide," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
