<HEADLINE> London Stock Market at Five Month High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON January 5 (Xinhua) - UK's FTSE 100 has joined the New
Year rally on world markets Tuesday as merger hopes and a robust
start to Wall Street lifted it to a five-month closing high.
</P>
<P>
The leading index closed up 79 points at 5958, although off its
highs for the day.
</P>
<P>
The market took little notice of a growing view that the Bank
of England will hold UK interest rates steady this week rather
than ease policy as many have been hoping.
</P>
<P>
Telecoms were again the market's shining light, as shares were
puffed on the back of strong subscriber figures unveiled by
Vodafone and Orange.
</P>
<P>
Vodafone admitted that it is in talks with US telecoms group
AirTouch about a merger. AirTouch has already been the subject of
a 45bn US dollars bid from Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
Compare with London, European markets were in a more cautious
mood after Monday's big rallies sparked by a bout of
euro-euphoria.
</P>
<P>
Germany's Xetra Dax index lost ground Tuesday as investors took
a more somber view after euro-euphoria had sent the index more
than 5 percent higher the day before.
</P>
<P>
The index ended 26.95 points down, or 0.51 percent at 5263.41.
"People are still cautious, choosing to consolidate rather than
head on up," a trader said.
</P>
<P>
Paris stocks notched up healthy gains in choppy trade on
Tuesday, the index still buoyant but in a more reflective mood
after a 5 percent jump on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Cac 40 index closed up 53.28 points, or 1.28 percent at
4200.78 points. "People felt the market got carried away on Monday
and ran up too quickly to give them the chance to buy in the
stocks they want in this year's portfolios," said a trader.
</P>
<P>
Observers believe that disappointment that Wall Street failed
to follow the rising lead set by European bourses subdued trade a
little, and the forthcoming earnings season was another worry.
</P>
</TEXT>
