<HEADLINE> Blue-Chips Captures Broad Gains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 5 (Xinhua) -- Despite a sharp drop in the
U.S. dollar against the Japanese yen, blue-chips captured broad
gains at the New York Stock Exchange Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed at 9,311.19, up 126.92.
During today's session, the Dow index was pushed as high as
9,338.00, close to its record closing high of 9,374.27 last Nov.
23.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four of the 30 Dow Jones industrial components were
higher at the close, including IBM, Alcoa, Procter &AMP; Gamble and
United Technologies.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index was up 16.68 at 1,244.78 while
the technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index up 43.22 to 2,251.17
in record territory.
</P>
<P>
Stock investors didn't view the dollar's drop against the yen
as critical because the dollar was stronger against the new
European currency, euro.
</P>
<P>
On the New York Foreign Exchange, the dollar was trading at
111.21 yen, down from 112.07 on Monday, which was not seen since
October 1996. The euro was quoted at 1.1771 dollars down from
1.1806 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Currencies of the 11 European countries are tied to the euro at
a fixed rate because they are no longer traded separately since
the inauguration of the single currency Monday. Based on the euro
rate Tuesday, the dollar was worth: 1.6617 german marks, up from
1.6567 Monday; 1.3712 Swiss francs, up from 1.3673; 5.5741 French
francs, up from 5.5556; 1,644.74 Italian lire, up from 1,639.34.
</P>
<P>
The british pound was trading at 1.6554 dollars, down from
1.6570 dollars, while the dollar was quoted at 1.5140 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.5268. 
</P>
</TEXT>
