<DOCNO> XIE19990106.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Americans Foresee Financial Flabbiness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES January 5 (Xinhua) -- One-third of Americans
predict that their finances will be in no better shape by the year
2000 than they are now, even with the soaring stock market and the
strong economy.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey released Tuesday, 22 percent of Americans
said the biggest obstacle in achieving fiscal fitness for 2000 is
lack of time. Other obstacles include too much debt such as credit
card debt, impulse spending and not enough financial know-how. Six
percent cited dreams of winning the lottery.
</P>
<P>
The survey of over 1,000 adults in November 1998 was sponsored
by Quicken, a California-based personal finance software program.
</P>
<P>
Quicken said in a report that only 40 percent of Americans
surveyed actually plan to set any financial goals for the year
2000. For those who have plans, half indicate that their goal will
be for future fiscal needs, including retirement, money in the
bank and for a college education. Additionally, more than
one-quarter of adults look to make large purchases, including a
house, expensive vacation and a car. However, it is only the
remaining 21 percent that plan to pay off credit card debt and
their mortgage.
</P>
<P>
When it comes to financial priorities, the generation gap
widens, Quicken said. While adults 35 years or older are more
likely than their younger counterparts to cite retirement as their
financial priority, those under 35 are more likely to set a goal
for the purchase of a home. In addition, paying off credit card
debt is more important to people 35 years of age or older. Yet,
saving money is more important to people under 35.
</P>
<P>
One of the suggestions Quicken offered is saving on a regular
basis and reinvesting interest or dividends. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
